Hey Candace,

¬†

Sometimes no matter how much you loved a job or how much you‚Äôve invested yourself into it‚Ä¶

¬†

You outgrow it.

¬†

And something deeper starts to call you.

¬†

But that transition can be one of the hardest things we have to face.

One of my students came to me at this place in her life‚Ä¶

¬†

Elham thought she had her dream career.

She was a teacher who loved supporting students, guiding parents, pouring her heart into others.

¬†

That‚Äôs what gave her life meaning.

¬†

But over time, something shifted.

¬†

She started craving something new, more flexible and with more freedom.

¬†

But she didn‚Äôt just want to tutor or teach again.

She wanted a rewarding new career path ( https://pages.jayshettycoaching.com/rewarding-career-video-bau-e/?el=RNC-email-outgrown-172-3&utm_campaign_name=JSCS%3A+Prospects+Week+172-3&utm_content_name=Outgrown+your+career%2C+Name%3F&utm_medium_name=email_action&utm_source_name=customer.io )‚Ä¶

¬†

Without losing her purpose.

¬†

That‚Äôs when she found my school and fell in love with coaching.

¬†

The more she learned about it‚Ä¶

¬†

The more pieces of her life started to fit together in a way they never had before.

¬†

It wasn‚Äôt about starting over.

¬†

She didn‚Äôt have to reinvent herself to move forward.

¬†

Coaching was the natural next step from the career she loved.

¬†

A new chapter that aligned with her purpose - and expanded it.

¬†

All those years of listening‚Ä¶

¬†

Of encouraging‚Ä¶

¬†

Of helping people feel seen and safe?

¬†

That love wasn‚Äôt wasted.

It became the foundation of her new chapter as a coach.

Now, she‚Äôs building a rewarding new coaching career where she still supports people deeply.

¬†

But with more freedom, more clarity, and more joy than she ever had before.

¬†

If you‚Äôre stuck with a feeling that your heart is in the right place - but your career no longer fits.

¬†

Like you‚Äôve outgrown where you are now, but don‚Äôt know what to do next‚Ä¶

¬†

Upcoming API change: New io_ready field for Block Storage volumesEffective date: November 12, 2025


We’re adding a new field, io_ready, to the Linode Block Storage (Volumes) API. This field indicates whether a volume is currently able to perform I/O (input/output) operations, helping you confirm operational readiness after volume attachment.


Why this change? Previously, a linode_id appearing in the API response did not always confirm that a volume was fully attached and ready. The new io_ready field provides accurate confirmation. This is particularly useful in the context of IAM (identity and access management) where an authorized block storage user may not have permission to view the Linode ID after volume attachment.

Details:
	- Field Name: io_ready
	- Type: Boolean (true | false)
	- Location: Top level of each volume object
	- Backward Compatibility: Fully backward compatible (additive change; no impact to existing schema or behavior)
Example API Response:

 
JSON{

  "id":12345,

  "label":"my-volume",

  "linode_id":12346,

  "linode_label":"linode123",

  "status":"active",

  "region":"us-east",

  "filesystem_path":"/dev/disk/by-id/scsi-0Linode_Volume_my-volume",

  "hardware_type":"nvme",

  "encryption":"enabled",

  "size":30,

  "created":"2018-01-01T00:01:01",

  "updated":"2018-01-01T00:01:01",

  "tags":["example tag","another example"],

  "io_ready":true
}


No action is required. The change will automatically be available through the Volumes API starting November 12, 2025.



 

 
 Lish SSH access deprecationDeprecation date: Q2 2026


 As part of ongoing platform modernization, we want to provide early notification that Lish access through SSH will be deprecated in Q2 2026.


 The Lish Console (Linode Shell) provides direct console access to your Linodes, allowing you to run commands, install software, and configure applications. While SSH-based access will be retired, web-based console access will remain available and enhanced. We are sharing this update well in advance and will provide additional transition details closer to the deprecation date.

Hey Candace,

¬†

I just heard one of my students talking about how, before they joined my school, they thought coaching = mentoring.

¬†

But they‚Äôre actually very different.

¬†

Winston, one of my students¬†from Ontario, Canada, found this out when he joined my school last year.

¬†

He‚Äôd built a lifetime of experience and knowledge in high-level and senior corporate roles.

¬†

And now he felt called to share with others in a more meaningful way.

¬†

He thought that meant coaching.

¬†

But what he discovered inside¬†my coaching Certification School ( https://pages.jayshettycoaching.com/ovsl-video-bau-e/?el=OVSL-email-not-mentoring-173-2&utm_campaign_name=JSCS%3A+Prospects+Week+173-2&utm_content_name=coaching+%E2%89%A0+mentoring&utm_medium_name=email_action&utm_source_name=customer.io )¬†flipped his idea of coaching on its head.

¬†

You see‚Ä¶

¬†

‚ùå Winston discovered that¬†life coaching is NOT about teaching.

¬†

‚úÖ It‚Äôs about empowering others to find answers within themselves - not telling them how to live their life.

¬†

Before joining my school, he had no idea coaching could be used this way.

¬†

That it was NOT about how smart or successful you are.

¬†

But¬†how well you apply specific life coaching techniques¬†that help others open doors within themselves.

This perspective shift alongside his new life coaching skills helped Winston¬†serve his clients in a profound new way.

¬†

And also helped him serve himself - through self-reflection and self-auditing.

¬†

If you want to find out if you have what it takes to coach like this‚Ä¶

Watch this short video ( https://pages.jayshettycoaching.com/ovsl-video-bau-e/?el=OVSL-email-not-mentoring-173-2&utm_campaign_name=JSCS%3A+Prospects+Week+173-2&utm_content_name=coaching+%E2%89%A0+mentoring&utm_medium_name=email_action&utm_source_name=customer.io )¬†that walks you through what coaching is - and how to know if it‚Äôs the right next step for you.

********************************
Supabase Update ‚Äî October 2025
********************************

Hey there üëã,

Here‚Äôs everything that happened with Supabase in the last month.

Coming to Lisbon WebSummit? Join us ( https://supabase.link/lisbon-hack ) for an epic 2-day hackathon! Details below.

**************************
Experience Supabase Select
**************************

Supabase Select was our first user conference and we welcomed hundreds of developers to Y Combinator Headquarters in San Francisco. Here is the news you may have missed:

* Supabase raised its Series E [Blog Post ( https://supabase.com/blog/supabase-series-e )]
* Members of the Supabase Community will be able to invest in Supabase
* 1000 Y Combinator companies are running on Supabase [Blog Post ( https://supabase.com/blog/1000-yc-companies )]

[Watch the main stage ( https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OaABqBG732Y )] [Watch the build stage ( https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GbBGYNNMWCg&t=36s )]

**************************
Supabase Remote MCP Server
**************************

You can now connect your Supabase projects with your AI coding agents using our remote HTTP-hosted MCP server.

[Blog Post] ( https://supabase.com/blog/remote-mcp-server )

******************************
Login with Solana and Ethereum
******************************

Supabase Auth now supports login with Solana and login with Ethereum.

[Blog Post ( https://supabase.com/blog/login-with-solana-ethereum )]

*******************
PostgREST 13 is out
*******************

It includes API and Observability improvements for both new and old projects.

[Blog Post ( https://supabase.com/blog/postgrest-13-release )]

*************************
Supabase Select Hackathon
*************************

We were excited to host 150 developers at Y Combinator Headquarters for the Supabase Select Hackathon. The winner was Repatch, an AI-generated patch notes tool for your GitHub repo, turned into beautiful release newsletters.

**************************
Hack with us at WebSummit!
**************************

Coming to Lisbon WebSummit? Join us for a two-day hackathon and build with the world‚Äôs foremost builders at the Supabase Lisbon AI Hackathon. Supabase is proud to be a part of Lisbon AI Week.

[Apply Now ( https://supabase.link/lisbon-hack )] [Learn about Lisbon AI Week ( https://lisbonaiweek.com/ )]

‚Ää

---------------------------
Quick Product Announcements
---------------------------

*
We've consolidated all Supabase JS client libraries into a unified monorepo at¬†supabase/supabase-js ( https://github.com/supabase/supabase-js ). Nothing changes for users, but contributors should take note. [GitHub ( https://github.com/orgs/supabase/discussions/39197 )]
*
Iceberg writes are now available via Foreign Data Wrappers. [GitHub ( https://github.com/supabase/wrappers/pull/506 )]
*
We made a tiny update to the Supabase UI Library to switch from stock shadcn to the Supabase starter. Gives you a lot more out of the box. [Twitter ( https://x.com/saltcod/status/1975546349626990886 )]
*
AI reasoning is now available in the Supabase Dashboard. [Twitter ( https://x.com/kiwicopple/status/1975693885272908072 )]

------------------
Made with Supabase
------------------

* Supabricks - One-click Supabase admin panel [Website ( https://www.supabricks.com/ )]
*
RooRooRoo - Website Watcher that notifies users via email or SMS when content appears, disappears, or errors happen [Website ( https://www.roorooroo.com/ )] [GitHub ( https://github.com/johnstonmatt/roorooroo-app )]
*
Market Research On Demand - Generate a multi-page market research report on any industry, with comprehensive in-line citations, reasoning, and excerpts [Website ( https://www.aimarketresearch.app/ )] [GitHub ( https://github.com/khushishelat/market-research-demo )]
*
Drawcraft - Create Custom¬†Drawing Images¬†in Seconds [Website ( https://drawcraft.io/ )]
*
CodeInn - an AI-powered coding assistant [Website ( https://codeinn.mscodee.com/ )] [GitHub ( https://github.com/mscode07/CodeINN )]
*
PodPrompt - Break down podcasts into summaries, highlights, and social-ready content [Website ( https://23-podprompt.paarad.org/ )]

--------------------
Community Highlights
--------------------

* Create real-time notifications in a matter of minutes with Next.js App Router and Supabase Realtime [Blog ( https://codecryrepeat.hashnode.dev/easy-real-time-notifications-with-supabase-realtime )]
*
The ‚ÄúEgoless‚Äù Company Culture that Powers Supabase with CEO Paul Copplestone [YouTube ( https://youtu.be/GSw4b6y2WnI?feature=shared )]
* How I used AI inside Figma to design, prototype, and connect a real backend without writing code [Blog ( https://medium.com/activated-thinker/i-built-a-to-do-app-in-minutes-using-figma-make-and-supabase-948386d31c62 )]
*
I've built a reusable Team component for Next.js 14 using Supabase [Blog ( https://guillaumeduhan.hashnode.dev/ive-build-a-reusable-team-component-for-nextjs-14-using-supabase )] [YouTube ( https://youtu.be/LNHWIbTEqNs?feature=shared )]
*
How I Replaced My Entire Backend With Supabase in 3 Hours ‚Äî Real Talk, Real Code [Blog ( https://dev.to/ekwoster/how-i-replaced-my-entire-backend-with-supabase-in-3-hours-real-talk-real-code-9bi )]

We're Hiring
------------

Come join one of the fastest-growing open source projects ever ü§ó

column7: ü§î You‚Äôre Not Lost‚ÄîYou‚Äôre in a Liminal Space
column9:
Hey Candace,

Hope you had a relaxing weekend üôè

As I mentioned in LifeNotes (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/5qu5ex8krot7hnzzd9qf6h9mlvl44tn/l2heh6ul4rqz07ug/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL25ld3NsZXR0ZXIv
) on Friday, I was feeling pretty rubbish last week with some
sort of cold or flu but the weekend was a good chance to properly
recharge so I‚Äôm back into the swing of things this week üí™

But anyway I wanted to talk about an analogy that I heard
recently that‚Äôs really stuck with me‚Äîso I thought I‚Äôd share it
with you all here.

I want you to imagine you‚Äôre on a plane. And when you really
think about your in-flight experience, it can feel pretty
terrifying. You‚Äôre not the one flying the plane, you‚Äôve got
absolutely no control, and you‚Äôre basically speeding through the
sky in a giant metal tube. üò®

Now this moment of feeling in between two different destinations
is what‚Äôs called a liminal space.

If you feel lost and uncertain after finishing school or uni
because you‚Äôre not yet sure where to start with your
career‚Äîthat‚Äôs a perfect example of a liminal space. Another
liminal space is that time after you‚Äôve quit your job but haven‚Äôt
yet figured out what‚Äôs next. Or, when you find yourself in a new
city but haven‚Äôt yet built new routines or found new friends.

Fun fact, the word liminal actually comes from the Latin term
‚Äúlimen‚Äù, which means threshold. But on a bad note, liminal spaces
tend to always feel pretty uncomfortable.

I first heard about this idea when I spoke to Anne-Laure Le
Cunff. Anne‚Äôs a neuroscientist, former Google executive, and
author of the book, Tiny Experiments (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/5qu5ex8krot7hnzzd9qf6h9mlvl44tn/m2h7h6u39e27gpcl/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL3RpbnlleHBlcmltZW50cw==
), which I‚Äôve already mentioned a few times in this newsletter -
it‚Äôs just such a wonderfully written, evidence-based guide to
dealing with uncertain chapters in your life.

And trust me, I‚Äôve experienced plenty of moments when I don‚Äôt
feel like I‚Äôm making the right decisions and I‚Äôm not exactly sure
where I‚Äôm going. üìç

Back when I spoke to Anne here in Hong Kong, I found myself stuck
at a crossroads. I was deep in the throes of like, do I dive
deeper into the software stuff, keep going with the whole YouTube
thing, write another book, or try and do something even bigger?

But just having the terminology to label this time in my life as
a liminal space was hugely transformative. It also lifted a huge
weight off my shoulders, because I was like, ‚ÄúAh, I‚Äôm in a
liminal space. It‚Äôs normal to feel uncomfortable, and it‚Äôs ok for
me to feel like I‚Äôm not doing the right thing.‚Äù

The majority of us‚Äîwhen stuck with no real plan or meaningful
goals‚Äîrush to ‚Äúfigure things out‚Äù and move forwards as quickly as
possible. And from an evolutionary perspective, trying to find
safety as soon as possible makes total sense. Our brains
literally evolved to hate uncertainty, because in the past, not
knowing where your next meal was coming from was a legit threat
to survival.

But this totally backfires in our modern lives, because being in
a liminal space isn‚Äôt dangerous. It‚Äôs just a bit disorienting.
üòµ‚Äçüí´

In fact, one of Anne‚Äôs key insights from the book is that you
shouldn‚Äôt try to escape liminal spaces. Instead, it‚Äôs best to
embrace them. Because that‚Äôs exactly where all the growth tends
to happen.

And if we go back to our aeroplane analogy, there‚Äôs actually
another way to experience flying through the sky at hundreds of
miles per hour - a rare space of solitude.

You've got no Wi-Fi, no one to call or message, and no
interruptions. But you can finally read the book that‚Äôs been
collecting dust on your TBR list, or just spend time journaling
out your thoughts. üí≠

So if you‚Äôre feeling a bit lost right now, the first thing to do
is acknowledge that you‚Äôre in a liminal space. Then, you can
start navigating the uncertainty, which is exactly what the whole
Vision component of LifeOS (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/5qu5ex8krot7hnzzd9qf6h9mlvl44tn/dphehmuek5dm49sl/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWxpbWluYWxfMTkmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPXByb2R1Y3RpdmVub3Rlcw==
) is all about.

I break this down into three practical tools to help you figure
out what‚Äôs next‚Äîone of which is your Life Compass. This is all
about figuring out what you want your life to look like and
working backwards to define your goals for the next 3-10 years,
and setting quests to help you get started right now.

If that sounds useful to you, you can click here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/5qu5ex8krot7hnzzd9qf6h9mlvl44tn/dphehmuek5dm49sl/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWxpbWluYWxfMTkmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPXByb2R1Y3RpdmVub3Rlcw==
) to find out more. ‚≠ê

Hope you have a great week ahead!

Ali xx

HeyGen ( https://app.heygen.com/?utm_source=campaign&utm_medium=email&utm_campaign=nav&utm_campaign=Rebrand+Launch+-+9.16+-+free+users+%28created+within+30+days%29&utm_content=Rebrand+Launch+-+9.16&utm_medium=email_action&utm_source=customerio )A new chapter at HeyGen.

( https://x.com/joshua_xu_/status/1967951859500437855?utm_campaign=Rebrand+Launch+-+9.16+-+free+users+%28created+within+30+days%29&utm_content=Rebrand+Launch+-+9.16&utm_medium=email_action&utm_source=customerio )Hi there,

Five years ago, our co-founders Joshua Xu and Wayne Liang started HeyGen with a simple belief: everyone has a story to tell. That‚Äôs why we set out to democratize video creation so that more people could create with confidence.¬†

Today, we‚Äôre taking a leap forward.

Meet our Video Agent! Now in public beta

( https://app.heygen.com/video-agent?utm_campaign=Rebrand+Launch+-+9.16+-+free+users+%28created+within+30+days%29&utm_content=Rebrand+Launch+-+9.16&utm_medium=email_action&utm_source=customerio )
The HeyGen Video Agent is your creative operating system. From a single prompt, it creates a complete, publishable video for all your needs. Script, casting, visuals, voice, pacing, captions, edit, and taste. End-to-end. Unlike generators that output clips or scenes, Video Agent does what a creative team would in one intelligent workflow, right in your browser.

Try it out here. ( https://app.heygen.com/video-agent?utm_campaign=Rebrand+Launch+-+9.16+-+free+users+%28created+within+30+days%29&utm_content=Rebrand+Launch+-+9.16&utm_medium=email_action&utm_source=customerio )

To accelerate this mission, HeyGen has acquired Alisa ( https://www.heygen.com/blog/bin-liu-joins-heygen?utm_campaign=Rebrand+Launch+-+9.16+-+free+users+%28created+within+30+days%29&utm_content=Rebrand+Launch+-+9.16&utm_medium=email_action&utm_source=customerio ), a pioneer in intelligent multimedia agents, and Bin Liu, Alisa‚Äôs co-founder and CEO, is joining HeyGen to lead Video Agent.

What this means for you

Video is becoming the default language at work and in life. This means that explaining, persuading, and teaching must be visual, personal, and simple. By integrating Alisa‚Äôs technology, HeyGen adds an intelligent creative layer that follows your directives, standardizes quality, protects your brand, and ships ready-to-publish videos at scale.¬†

You‚Äôll also notice a refreshed HeyGen brand in the app reflecting where we‚Äôre headed in this new chapter. Thank you for trusting us with your message. Your stories give HeyGen our purpose. Come help shape this new era with us, and together, let‚Äôs free your story.

Excited to see what you'll create,

The HeyGen Team

column7: Candace, you're invited by IxDF New York City to attend ‚ÄúInfluence Without Authority: Moving From Reactivity to Proactivity as an IC Researcher‚Äù
column9:
Interaction Design Foundation logo [https://public-images.interaction-design.org/emails/brand/v5/ixdf-logo-for-header.jpg]
 YOU'RE INVITED: "INFLUENCE WITHOUT AUTHORITY: MOVING FROM REACTIVITY TO
PROACTIVITY AS AN IC RESEARCHER"
Dear Candace,

Great news - IxDF New York City hereby invites you to a meetup on 16th Oct 2025
02:00 PM EDT organized by Neha Scher-Shah. See all details further down.

 Great news ‚Äî IxDF New York City is hosting a meetup on 16th Oct 2025 02:00 PM
EDT, organized by Neha Scher-Shah. You're warmly invited to join! Full details
are below. 

 This isn't just another event ‚Äî it's a doorway to valuable insights, new
friendships, and real professional growth. Big things often start small ‚Äî and it
all begins by simply showing up. 

 Bring your friends along ‚Äî IxDF Local Group meetups are free and open to
everyone! Even better: you can give them 3 free months of IxDF membership, and 
earn free membership for yourself
[https://email.mailgun.interaction-design.org/c/eJxsyruOhSAQANCvgU4jw0sKim38DxxncJLrI0jW399my9uenC0nXolnTdlEn9KcQjR6z9GEOANAioTWICV2m6eyRlydsb5oyRwLW2-p2M3Z4NGxsd4AMDPMwQXlJjk7tYJdrnPY6JF6jler-pP33u9H2R8Fi4Llfd_xe1WwHHSs1B4FS6U-cCMa_mmXW7dcBK-Cu5wVJvDKTfUo8hnxOvRvhr8AAAD__3ymRyQ] 
in the process. 

WHY ATTEND IXDF MEETUPS?
 * Your network is your net worth‚Äîjoin us to learn, network, and find
   opportunities.
 * Connect with professionals who can open new doors.
 * Be part of a community where small meetups lead to big opportunities.
 * Get help and advice from our community. And give back.
 * Come as you are! Design skills are not just for designers‚Äîthey're for
   everyone in any job, any industry.
 * Be part of a caring and supportive community.
 * It's free for everyone to attend‚Äîso bring your friends who are not IxDF
   members.

INFLUENCE WITHOUT AUTHORITY: MOVING FROM REACTIVITY TO PROACTIVITY AS AN IC
RESEARCHER
16th Oct 2025 02:00 PM EDT
https://luma.com/ranwjozp

16 at 11 am PST, Nikki Anderson (User Research Strategist) joins us for a free
session on how to move from reactivity to real... Attend This IxDF Meetup

The more you help your community, the more you gain in terms of credibility,
network, career opportunities and positivity.

credibility, a stronger network, unexpected career opportunities, and lasting 
positive energy.

others to join the meetup ‚Äî it takes just a minute!

column7: Join the September Cohort ‚Äì Apply by May 14
column9:
<https://ischoolonline.berkeley.edu/data-science/>

ACCESS YOUR APPLICATION >>
<https://apply.datascience.berkeley.edu/signup>
 
"I chose datascience@berkeley because of the flexibility offered by the program, as well as the well-rounded curriculum. I like that the program was not simply about coding and data systems. The emphasis on aspects of data science with consideration for real-world application, like ethics and communication, created an entire package that appealed to me. The ability to learn remotely from an institution like UC Berkeley was also compelling, as I could structure my course work each semester around my personal and professional life while attending such a prestigious institution."
 
Michael Amodeo, datascience@berkeley student
 
HEAR MORE FROM STUDENTS >>
<http://datascience.berkeley.edu/experience/student-profiles/>
 
The Master of Information and Data Science (MIDS) program is attracting data science professionals from across the country and around the world. Get to know some of the outstanding students <https://datascience.berkeley.edu/experience/student-profiles/> earning their degrees online at the UC Berkeley School of Information.
 
The final application deadline for our September 2025 class start is May 14, so now is the time to submit your application <https://apply.datascience.berkeley.edu/signup>. If you have any questions, please contact your Admissions Counselor at 855-678-6437 or slee2@datascience.berkeley.edu.
 
Sincerely,

column7: Stop Relying on One Income Stream (Here‚Äôs What to Do Instead)
column9:
Hey Candace,

Hope you‚Äôre having a great week so far ‚ò∫Ô∏è

A few weeks back, you may remember my email where I talked all
about brand sponsorships - when to start accepting them and the
all-important question of how much you should actually charge -
but what‚Äôs important to realise is that sponsorships are just one
piece of a much bigger monetisation puzzle.

As a creator, your goal should be to diversify your revenue
streams. Why? Well, it‚Äôs pretty obvious, but I like to think of
your creator business as a river.

If that river dries up or gets blocked, then you‚Äôre no longer
profitable. But if you‚Äôve got multiple streams feeding into that
one main river, then if any one of them has issues, you‚Äôre still
afloat. The business keeps generating cash and you‚Äôre not lying
awake at 3am panicking about a single income source disappearing
üòÖ

When I first started as a YouTuber back in the day, it took me 8
months to make any sort of money on the platform at all, and then
for about 6-12 months after that, the only money I made was
through YouTube ads and brand sponsorships.

Both of those were fundamentally dependent on the YouTube
algorithm and my upload consistency, so over time, we started to
properly diversify with things like affiliates, online courses
like PTYA (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/0vu4o3k67va9h9gm4m5blhv0egk55snh95n7l/48hvh7ummwvlnvfq/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWxpYWJkYWFsLmNvbS9wYXJ0LXRpbWUteW91dHViZXItYWNhZGVteS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWNnXzE1JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jcmVhdG9ybm90ZXM=
), and both physical and digital products.

So when you‚Äôre thinking about building a sustainable and
profitable creator business with diverse revenue streams, there
are really 2 main approaches you can take: selling other people‚Äôs
stuff and selling your own stuff.

Selling your own stuff means creating physical products (like
merch or books), digital products (like templates, PDFs, or
presets), or offering services (like consulting or coaching).
We‚Äôve covered that quite a bit in recent emails (and I‚Äôm going to
be diving into that side of things even further over the next
couple of months), so today I want to focus on selling other
people‚Äôs stuff, which breaks down into 3 main categories.

1Ô∏è‚É£ Ads - This includes things like Google AdSense or TikTok
Creator Fund, and the beauty of ads is that they‚Äôre completely
passive. You just create content and the platform handles
everything for you pretty much, but the downside is that the
rates aren‚Äôt anything spectacular and you have very little
control over them.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Affiliates - This is where you recommend products and get a
commission when people buy through your link. Amazon Associates
is the most obvious one that comes to mind but tbh that‚Äôs the
least interesting option because the commission rates are pretty
rubbish (like 1-4%), and the more interesting approach is to
directly reach out to brands you genuinely love and ask if they
have an affiliate programme.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Sponsorships - Here we‚Äôve got the classic ‚Äúthis video is
brought to you by‚Ä¶‚Äù situation. A brand essentially pays you a
flat fee, usually expecting a certain number of views or
impressions (but not always), and you create an integration
within your content.

Yes, sponsorships can be lucrative, but they‚Äôre also the most
time-intensive to negotiate and manage. And as a small creator
when you‚Äôre just getting started, brand sponsorships can feel
completely out of reach when you don‚Äôt hit the arbitrary views or
follower thresholds that most brands require.

That‚Äôs why my team, Izzy (my wife), and I wanted to fix this, and
we‚Äôve built a completely free platform called CreatorGrid (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/0vu4o3k67va9h9gm4m5blhv0egk55snh95n7l/wnh2h6uqqmn737al/aHR0cHM6Ly9jcmVhdG9yZ3JpZC5pby9jcmVhdG9ycz91dG09Q1JFQVRPUk5PVEVTX0xBVU5DSF8x
), which helps creators of any size grow and monetise their
audience.

When you join, you basically get access to flexible brand deals,
which you can literally sign up for no matter your following
size. So whether you have 10 followers or 10 million followers,
you can make content promoting brands you already know and love,
and get paid based on how it performs.

How it works in a bit more detail is that you create content (on
either YouTube Shorts, Instagram Reels, or TikTok) promoting one
of the brands on the platform, and if your content gets approved,
you‚Äôre paid based on the number of views you get.

When we trialled this with our own app Voicepal, several creators
made over $2,000 in their first week, which is incredible. And
what I think makes this even better is that there‚Äôs no
application process, no negotiation, and no awkward
back-and-forth trying to convince brands you‚Äôre worth working
with.

So if you want to give it a go, you can sign up here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/0vu4o3k67va9h9gm4m5blhv0egk55snh95n7l/wnh2h6uqqmn737al/aHR0cHM6Ly9jcmVhdG9yZ3JpZC5pby9jcmVhdG9ycz91dG09Q1JFQVRPUk5PVEVTX0xBVU5DSF8x
).

We‚Äôre also building out a whole growth side of the platform too
where the end goal is to have a bunch of free AI tools that
basically replicate having a full content team behind you. This
will help you generate ideas, write hooks, create outlines, and
optimise your content based on what actually performs well, but
as a heads up, we‚Äôre still in the beta phase with this right now.

Anyway, feel free to check it out and because it‚Äôs still very
much a work in progress, I‚Äôd genuinely love to hear your feedback
- what works well? What could be better? Send us an email at
creators@creatorgrid.io (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/0vu4o3k67va9h9gm4m5blhv0egk55snh95n7l/08hwhgu22nvek5up/bWFpbHRvOmNyZWF0b3JzQGNyZWF0b3JncmlkLmlv
) and let us know how you‚Äôre finding it.

Have a great rest of your week üôå

Ali xx

column7: Welcome to the LangGraph Essentials Course!
column9:
96

Welcome to the Building Ambient Agents with LangGraph Course!

Welcome to our LangGraph Essentials course!

LangGraph is a powerful framework designed for building agentic
and multi-agent applications. Distinct from the LangChain
package, LangGraph‚Äôs core design philosophy is to help developers
add better precision and control into agentic workflows, suitable
for the complexity of real-world systems.

In this Quickstart course, you‚Äôll explore the essential building
blocks of LangGraph by creating simple workflows, and then build
a sample agent to tie it all together.

I hope you enjoy the course and gain the skills to master
LangGraph, so you can create powerful, production-ready agents.

Hunter Lovell
Course Instructor & Software Engineer at LangChain

Hey friends,

Got two sources of Big News for you this week!

Firstly, a Big Piece of News is that I‚Äôm hosting a live 6-week
bootcamp from 1st Aug to 12th Sept. It‚Äôs called the $1k Challenge
- a 6-week online bootcamp to help you make your first $1,000
online, while teaching you the key Income Generation Skills you
can use for the rest of your life. If you‚Äôre a beginner to making
money on the internet, and you like the idea of building an
income stream outside of your day job, and maybe working towards
financial independence someday, I‚Äôd love for you to join the
waitlist to learn more, and be notified when it‚Äôs ready for
enrolment. Click here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/27u74ok3xrboh8om4x8s0ig658744hghgkmn3/7qh7h2u9m403q2h9/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3RoZS0xay1jaGFsbGVuZ2UvP2xtLWdh
) to sign up :)

And now‚Ä¶the Very Big Piece of News is that I‚Äôm now a dad! Our
baby girl was born a few weeks ago and we‚Äôve just made the news
public on Instagram (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/27u74ok3xrboh8om4x8s0ig658744hghgkmn3/owhkhwuw7845p2fq/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuaW5zdGFncmFtLmNvbS9wL0RMajZtcDlvQkVXLz9pZ3NoPU1XazJPSE16TTNRMFp6a3lOdyUzRCUzRA==
). She‚Äôs healthy and very cute and currently doesn‚Äôt do much
other than sleep, drink, wee, poo, cry and sort-of look around
with her neck in dodgy positions. I‚Äôm learning a whole new set of
skills around how to hold a baby, how to burp a baby, how to feed
a baby pumped-milk from the bottle, and reading a lot about baby
brain development, the importance of reading to them, a load of
stuff about sleep, and plenty more.

I‚Äôve just filmed a video about the whole experience so I won‚Äôt go
into more detail here, but this week I wanted to share a life
lesson I learned during the final trimester of my wife Izzy‚Äôs
pregnancy.

During that time, we were shopping for various baby supplies,
trying to get her nursery prepped ahead of the birth. Things
like: a crib, a pram, a car seat, a baby changing station,
figuring out what nappies to use and what other paraphernalia of
nappy changing we needed, muslin cloths, swaddles etc etc.

Like a good modern couple, Izzy and I split the workload in terms
of sorting baby supplies. She sorted all the breastfeeding and
pumping and bottles and sterilisers and all that stuff. I was in
charge of the travel and bedroom tech - the crib, pram, car seat
etc. Which was great because I love watching YouTube videos about
new tech, and after watching Sara Dietschy‚Äôs video about baby
gear recommendations, we bought almost everything she
recommended.

I was also in charge of sorting out the nappy changing station.
And this is where things started to go‚Ä¶ a little sub-optimally.

Izzy really wanted stuff to be sorted many weeks before the baby
was due, so that we wouldn‚Äôt be stressing closer to the time,
especially if the baby came early. I was‚Ä¶ shall we say, more
‚Äúlast minute‚Äù about things. My attitude was basically: ‚Äúit‚Äôs all
good, we‚Äôve got a department store 10 mins walk from our house,
we can always get stuff when we realise we need it, it‚Äôs not a
big deal‚Äù.

I didn‚Äôt actually say ‚Äúit‚Äôs not a big deal‚Äù of course - that‚Äôs
one of the phrases, along with ‚Äúcalm down‚Äù and ‚Äúyou‚Äôre
overreacting‚Äù that most married couples realise should be
permanently banned in the household if you want to have a
healthy, happy marriage. But‚Ä¶ even though I didn‚Äôt use those
specific words, my attitude was: ‚Äúit‚Äôs not a big deal, I can
figure this out closer to the time, how hard can it be‚Äù etc.

This approach, in productivity and business circles, is often
described as ‚ÄúJust in Time‚Äù. You do something, or buy something,
or research something, ‚Äújust in time‚Äù - ie: when you realise you
need the thing imminently. The alternative approach is often
described as ‚ÄúJust in Case‚Äù - where you prep stuff ahead of time,
in case you need it, rather than waiting until you actually do.

I thought I was going with the Just in Time approach, which is
generally how I do most things in life: ie: fairly last minute.
And initially I thought Izzy should just accept that, given that
she married me, and knew that this is how I like to do things,
and who cares if the nappy bin arrives 2 months before the baby
is due, or 2 days before the baby is due? Either way it‚Äôs still
in the house right?

Wrong. At least that‚Äôs what a friend told me, a friend who‚Äôs been
happily married for like 20 years. Here‚Äôs how he described it.
Paraphrased:

‚ÄúAli, your Just in Time Last Minute approach to things works
great when you‚Äôre building a startup. It‚Äôs nimble, it‚Äôs fast, it
means you save a lot of time that others would be spending
planning and analysing and overthinking. So it works fine when
you‚Äôre trying to grow your business.
But when it comes to your marriage, your home and your family
life, speed of execution and the ability to pivot at a moment‚Äôs
notice isn‚Äôt actually the goal. What your wife wants in this
season of life isn‚Äôt speed, it‚Äôs security (I realise this sounds
like AI, it isn‚Äôt lol). She wants to know that the house is ready
and prepared for baby‚Äôs arrival, and she doesn‚Äôt want to be
stressing about whether you have the right equipment, especially
while she‚Äôs under the strain of the final trimester. She‚Äôs hoping
that you, as her husband, can step up and SORT SHIT OUT ideally
without being asked. And if you ARE asked, that you SORT SHIT OUT
without needing to be reminded. This will help her feel SAFE and
SECURE.
So stop sabotaging your marriage by trying to use your
efficiency-productivity Only Do Things When They Become Urgent
toolkit. It works fine for growing a business, but is a terrible
way to approach building a healthy, safe, tranquil home for your
wife and family‚Äù.
Well damn. That was good advice. So I ran it by Izzy, and she
said (paraphrased):

‚ÄúWhoah yeah that‚Äôs spot on. That‚Äôs what I‚Äôve been trying to tell
you! When something‚Äôs on your todo list, I‚Äôd feel so much better,
and safer, and happier, if you dealt with the thing without
needing to be reminded of it. I‚Äôm happy to be in charge of the
household stuff broadly, but if I ask you to do or buy or
research something and you say you‚Äôre going to do it, I‚Äôd love if
I could feel like it‚Äôs now fully off my todo list. Right now,
when I ask you to do something, I still keep it on my own todo
list, and I remind myself to remind you about the thing a week
from now, because I know you probably won‚Äôt get round to it, and
you‚Äôll need a few nudges before it happens. I‚Äôd love it if things
could happen sooner than that, ideally without needing a
reminder. And if you know you won‚Äôt get around to doing
something, I‚Äôd much rather you let me know there and then, rather
than me feeling disappointed when you AGREE to do it and then it
isn‚Äôt done.‚Äù
Huh. Okay that makes a lot of sense.

After some more back and forth conversation about this, I came to
my own realisation: that when Izzy asks me to something, I should
ask the following follow-up question: ‚ÄúYep sure I can help with
that‚Ä¶ just to check, in an ideal world, would this be done like
TODAY, or like THIS WEEK, or like anytime in the next few weeks?‚Äù

I‚Äôve been using that line for months now, and it‚Äôs glorious. By
asking the question, I get a clear sense of what Izzy‚Äôs ideal
timeline for the project or task is, and it‚Äôs usually a little
speedier than my own internal timeline would‚Äôve been. I can then
decide if it‚Äôs something I want to agree to doing, and if I do
agree to it, then I‚Äôm agreeing to the timeline for it as well,
because if I don‚Äôt do it, she‚Äôs just going to do it herself, and
she‚Äôs got enough on her plate.

At least‚Ä¶ that‚Äôs the idea. I‚Äôm still not great at it, but it‚Äôs
improving.

And the insight from my happily-married friend about
Fast-and-Loose Startup Mode vs Steady-and-Secure Family Mode was
great too - I now (try my best) to keep that in mind when doing
home-related stuff and trying to separate that mode of operation
from what I continue doing with work-related stuff. Again, still
a work in progress, it takes time to change a deeply ingrained
habit, but it‚Äôs been going okay so far.

I guess the key message is that different contexts sometimes need
different approaches. The ‚Äúmove fast and break things‚Äù mentality
that works well for startups can ACTUALLY break things in your
marriage if you‚Äôre not careful hehe. And when your partner is
pregnant and preparing for a major life change, I suspect the
last thing they want is to feel like they can‚Äôt rely on you to
handle the stuff you‚Äôve committed to handling.

The question ‚Äúwhen would you ideally like this done?‚Äù has become
my secret weapon (amongst many others). It‚Äôs such a simple thing,
but it‚Äôs helped me realise that my default timeline for most
things is usually about 2-3x longer than what would actually be
helpful. And tbh, most of the time, doing something THIS WEEK
instead of NEXT MONTH doesn‚Äôt actually take that much more
effort, just a slight tweak in priorities.

Plus, I love it when Izzy asks or reminds me to do something and,
with a smug expression on my face, I‚Äôm like: ‚Äúbabe it‚Äôs already
handled‚Äù. She lights up. It‚Äôs great.

Anyway, in case you were wondering, the nappy changing stuff DID
INDEED arrive like 3 weeks before the baby was born. BUT‚Ä¶ I
obviously didn‚Äôt bother to setup the nappy bin, because why would
you bother unboxing and building it until you have a steaming
diaper on your hands?? Thankfully, Izzy‚Äôs mum (who was visiting
us at the time to help us prep for baby) decided to unbox and
build the bin‚Ä¶ only to realise that the manufacturer hadn‚Äôt
delivered a key part, and so it wasn‚Äôt actually functional‚Ä¶ which
we found out like 3 days before the baby was born‚Ä¶ so in the end,
we didn‚Äôt actually have a functional nappy bin until a week after
the baby got back home‚Ä¶ which was fine‚Ä¶ but not the best poster
child for my ‚Äújust do things at the last minute‚Äù approach to
life.

Have a great week!

Ali xx

View image: (https://media.beehiiv.com/cdn-cgi/image/fit=scale-down,format=auto,onerror=redirect,quality=80/uploads/asset/file/d10cf965-30eb-471e-8b5e-e6e6c8dbb631/DW-Newsletter-Quote.png?t=1762804756)
Caption: 


--------------------
# Q: What do I do when things are hard and I feel alone?

_‚ÄúWork is draining me right now, and I just don‚Äôt know what to do.‚Äù_

_‚ÄúMy relationship is falling apart, and I wish I had some guidance.‚Äù_

_‚ÄúI‚Äôm at a low point financially, and it feels like nobody knows or cares.‚Äù_

Why is it that when things feel the toughest, we feel the most isolated? What makes us feel so lonely when challenges come our way?

**I believe it‚Äôs because **[**we‚Äôre afraid of asking for help.**](https://www.youtube.com/shorts/RNPSd-p4VyE)** **

We‚Äôre scared of asking our parents.
We‚Äôre scared of asking our friends.
We‚Äôre scared of asking our brothers and sisters, our coworkers, our community members.

We‚Äôre scared that our problems aren‚Äôt big enough. That there are other people who have bigger problems, which somehow invalidate our own.

We‚Äôre scared that our problems aren‚Äôt real enough. That we _should_ be able to figure them out by now.

We‚Äôre scared that our problems aren‚Äôt valid enough. That everybody deals with this kind of thing, and we just need to get over it.

But, [as I described to Michelle Obama on her podcast a few months ago](https://youtu.be/AOdEx_k-Nz0): learning how to ask for help when you need it is one of the strongest things you can do. 

**Asking for help is a strength.**

Not asking for help can _feel_ like strength at first. But over time, it can become a quiet form of weakness, one that erodes connection, confidence, and trust in others.

We convince ourselves that if we ask for help, we‚Äôre somehow admitting to the world that we‚Äôre not perfect.

But here‚Äôs the thing. You‚Äôre not perfect. And nobody expects you to be.¬†

When you ask for support, you bring people in. You humanize yourself. You turn your suffering into an opportunity for connection. 

**The greatest power in your life is the people you‚Äôre surrounded by.¬†**

Think of your favorite people. Maybe a friend, a family member. What would you do if they came to you asking for _your_ help, big or small? You‚Äôd do it, without question.

Let them do the same for you.

_**Remember: **_Today marks Veterans Day in the U.S. and Remembrance Day in Canada. For those recognizing this day, may it be a moment of reflection, appreciation, and connection.







--------------------

True wellness isn't about a number on the scale ‚Äî it's about feeling your best every day. It‚Äôs having the energy for what you love, the mental clarity to stay focused, and the confidence that you‚Äôre truly caring for your body.

[Fay](https://www.faynutrition.com/find?utm_source=newsletter&utm_medium=email&utm_campaign=jayshetty_25_11) makes holistic, expert-led wellness accessible. --------------------
# Today‚Äôs Wiser Choice

We all have problems we face day in and day out: some big, some small. None of them has to be done totally on your own.

**Try This**: Make a list of the things you have to do that are really weighing you down. For example, you might have bills that you‚Äôre struggling to pay off. Or you might have a to-do list that‚Äôs longer than a CVS receipt. Or both.

Now write a second list. 

Who are the people in your life that are your biggest supporters? Maybe parents, maybe friends, maybe neighbors.

Are there people on that list you can ask for help? Maybe it‚Äôs as simple as calling them and talking about the problem. Because sometimes just being heard is enough.

column7: The final lesson ‚ÄúCourse Certificate, Final Networking, and Course Wrap-up‚Äù is now ready in your course ‚ÄúPersonas and User Research: Design Products and Services People Need and Want‚Äù
column9:
Great news, Candace, the final wrap-up lesson of the course is now available!

Well done for making it this far. We hope you‚Äôre ready to bring personas into your projects and turn real user needs into winning decisions.

We‚Äôre happy that 2,143 course-takers have joined our class so far, some of whom have scored more than 70% overall. If you‚Äôve completed the course and earned your Course Certificate, remember to download and display it on your LinkedIn profile, portfolio, and resume along with your unique link so recruiters can verify its authenticity. 

Take the final lesson and start generating your Course Certificate here: 

https://www.interaction-design.org/courses/personas-user-research-design-products-people-need 

Don‚Äôt worry if you haven‚Äôt completed the course. After all, this course (and all other courses from the Interaction Design Foundation) are created for busy people, and you‚Äôll have access to it for as long as you‚Äôre a member. Take your time and learn at your own pace‚Äîslow and steady wins the race. 

We hope you‚Äôre ready to reap the rewards that research-backed personas give you. Have you enjoyed the course? Do you have any feedback for us‚Äîpositive or otherwise? Please remember to respond to our course feedback, which you can find in the final lesson: 

https://www.interaction-design.org/courses/personas-user-research-design-products-people-need

column7: Learning Analytics and Artificial Intelligence (Online) M.S.Ed. - Final Deadline Announced!
column9:
July 15

                                      July 15 final deadline for Learning Analytics and Artificial Intelligence (Online) M.S.Ed. Program                                    





                                      Final Application Deadline:
                                      July 15, 2025                                    


                                      Dear Candace,

                                      Thank you for your interest in the University of Pennsylvania Graduate School of Education.

                                      We are very close to reaching our enrollment capacity for the Learning Analytics and Artificial Intelligence (Online) M.S.Ed. program for Fall 2025!

                                      As such, all applications and required materials for the Learning Analytics and Artificial Intelligence (Online) M.S.Ed. program must be submitted to the Office of Admissions and Financial Aid no later than 11:59 pm (ET) on Tuesday, July 15, 2025, to guarantee faculty review. If your application materials are received after this deadline, we will not be able to consider your application for the Fall 2025 term.
                                                                           

                                      If you have any questions about the application process or would like to have a conversation about potential study at GSE with one of our team's leaders, contact us <https://www.gse.upenn.edu/admissions/information> by email at admissions@gse.upenn.edu or by phone at (215) 898-6415.

                                      We look forward to reviewing your application!

                                      Sincerely,

October 22, 2025

If print‚Äôs not dead, who‚Äôs keeping it alive?
If print‚Äôs not dead, who‚Äôs

keeping it alive?

‚Ää
Far from fading, print is quietly being reinvented by the makers who never left its side. In a digital‚Äëfirst world obsessed with speed, a new generation of printmakers, publishers, and presses are proving that paper still has power, rooted in process, imperfection, and the tactile joy of something truly made by hand.

Also in this issue
* British rail gets a new face with the first national clock in 50 years
* Case study: How thoughtful UX turned a mental health app into a space for healing
* Dribbble Pros now have access to Client Work Analytics üìä

‚Ää

The hands behind the headlines: How modern printmakers are redefining what ‚Äúalive‚Äù means for print

As conversations about ‚Äúthe death of print‚Äù echo across the creative industry, this piece shifts focus to the people still giving the medium its pulse: the printmakers, small presses, and designers pushing the boundaries of ink, material, and time. From London‚Äôs Make‚ÄëReady to New York‚Äôs Small Editions and the pioneering Knust in the Netherlands, these studios are redefining craftsmanship for a generation raised on screens. Their work blends analogue precision with contemporary experimentation, bridging print and digital worlds while passing on endangered knowledge. Next week, Dickie and I are going to host something we've NEVER done before.

Next Tuesday, November 18th, Dickie and I will be kicking off something we've never done before...

The Write Your Way To Wealth LIVE challenge.

Over 3 days, we'll show you the 3 skills you need to master to become a Wealthy Writer (even if you have zero experience).

Write Your Way To Wealth: How To Build Your Dream Life As A Writer (In Just 3 Days)

So if you already know this is exactly what you need, click here to secure your spot.

Otherwise‚Ä¶

Here‚Äôs a quick overview of what we‚Äôre going to cover on this 3-day challenge:

üéØ Day 1: Positioning Masterclass (With AI)

In this 2-hour session, we‚Äôll cover:

‚Ä¢ What the top 1% of writers do differently to attract premium clients instead of chasing them‚Äîand why this one shift can 3x your rates overnight.

‚Ä¢ Why 90% of writers dilute their positioning trying to appeal to everyone‚Äîand the counterintuitive approach that makes landing ideal clients EASIER.

‚Ä¢ The quickest, easiest way to position yourself as an expert‚Äîeven if you don‚Äôt consider yourself a ‚Äúgood‚Äù writer.

‚Ä¢ How to build a "Niche Constellation" that maximizes opportunities without diluting your premium positioning (so you never run out of high-paying clients for your business).

‚Ä¢ The positioning secret that makes you the only logical choice for high-ticket clients in your niche (so you can stop competing on price with bargain basement writers off Upwork & Fiverr)

And tons more!

Plus, we‚Äôll share our Positioning AI Mega-Prompt to help you fill out your Positioning Identity 1-Pager so you can get extreme clarity on who you serve.

Which leads us nicely into the next day‚Ä¶

üéÅ Day 2: The Packaging & Pricing Blueprint

Once you have your Positioning nailed, it‚Äôs time to figure out how to package up your service so you can sell it for a premium (and we‚Äôre talking $5,000+ here!)

In this session, you‚Äôll discover:

‚Ä¢ The "Irresistible Offer Stack" framework that transforms any writing service into a $5,000+ package premium clients can't refuse.

‚Ä¢ What separates a $500 project from a $5,000 project‚Äîhint: it has nothing to do with word count or writing ‚Äúquality.‚Äù

‚Ä¢ Why the most successful writers refuse to write "whatever the client needs" ‚Äî and how this constraint actually triples their income.

‚Ä¢ The 5 ways to justify premium rates that have nothing to do with your experience level (you can use just 2 and double your prices).

‚Ä¢ How to create an offer so compelling that clients ask "when can we start?" instead of "how much does it cost?‚Äù

And a whole lot more.

We‚Äôll share a swipe file of the 3 top services you should be offering as a writer right now (so you know exactly what to sell!) and our Irresistible Offer Stack template so you can recreate these for yourself over and over again.

Alright, now you have your positioning dialled in and you know what you‚Äôre selling‚Ä¶ it‚Äôs time to find and land some clients!

üí∞ Day 3: Our $3,000,000 Prospecting Playbook

Collectively, we‚Äôve generated over $3,500,000 as ghostwriters (and worked with over 300+ industry leaders).

And not once did we ever feel ‚Äúsales-y.‚Äù

So, how do you go about finding and landing these high-ticket clients?

That‚Äôs what Day 3 is all about:

‚Ä¢ What top-earning writers know about sales that struggling writers don't‚Äîand why this skill matters more than your entire portfolio or writing ability.

‚Ä¢ Why cold outreach fails for 95% of writers‚Äîand the AI-powered approach that gets responses from busy executives.

‚Ä¢ If you hate "selling yourself," then you'll love this Free Consulting approach that has clients convincing themselves to hire you.

‚Ä¢ Following up once is enough, right? Wrong! Discover the follow-up sequence that converts "not right now" into closed deals.

‚Ä¢ How AI can help you close more deals‚Äîthe surprisingly effective system that turns call recordings into sales improvements.

And tons more!

Plus, we‚Äôll give you outreach message scripts that are working right now, our Sales Script Call template (which we‚Äôve used to sell $3,500,000+ of ghostwriting services), and our follow-up sequence framework so you can land more deals.

Then you can use our AI Sales Script review prompt to review your last (or next!) sales call to help you improve (and close more deals!).

Phew, that‚Äôs a lot!

But I wanted to make sure you get everything you need out of these 3 days so you can make money as a writer as quickly as possible.

Now, it doesn‚Äôt stop there‚Ä¶

‚Üí Because every day you‚Äôll also get:

‚Ä¢ ‚ÄúHomework‚Äù 1-pagers and tasks to help you implement all of the frameworks we share on the call a lot faster.

‚Ä¢ 3x Live Student Spotlights‚Äîinterviews with writers using these frameworks in their businesses RIGHT NOW to show you how they actually work in practice (like Carolene who went from your typical burned-out freelance writer to a highly-paid writer that could take her parents on a dream vacation).

‚Ä¢ Lifetime access to all the course materials and live session recordings so you can keep coming back to these over and over again.

Remember, each day, we'll go LIVE for 2-3 hours‚Äîand breaking down the exact frameworks, templates, and strategies our most successful students use.

And yes, you‚Äôll have the chance to ask us any question you want during our dedicated 30-minute Q&A blocks on all 3 days.

The best part?

It doesn't matter which writing path you choose‚Äîghostwriting, copywriting, content writing, newsletter writing‚Äîthese skills apply to ALL of them.

I‚Äôm going to share the 3 simple frameworks you need to become a wealthy writer‚Äîthe exact frameworks I wish I could‚Äôve given myself all those years ago, fresh out of college.

Now, don‚Äôt forget:

column7: [GoodBarber] Tip 9/9: Learn how to use notifications
column9:
Hi ,

A push notification is a short message to inform, engage, and attract users. ‚Ä®It's a great way to get a user to perform a certain action, notify users with last-minute news and much more. Most importantly, users don't have to be in the app or using their devices to receive them!
Beyond regular push notifications, did you know that you can also rely on the power of geo alerts to make your notifications smarter?

Push notifications

These notifications appear on your user's smartphone regardless of whether your app is open or not. Properly targeted, it is an efficient tool to inform, entertain, engage‚Ä¶ 
To learn more about how to use Push Notifications, click here (https://candaceux.goodbarber.app/manage/settings/help/0/99/).

Scheduled push

Save time! Set your own rules and deliver automatic push notifications for specific sections and even user groups, with our Scheduled push Extension (https://candaceux.goodbarber.app/manage/settings/help/54/204/).

Geofencing

These specific notifications rely on a technology which allows you to interact with your users through geo-alerts, based on their behavior within a designated geographical area. 
Learn how to set up Geofencing (https://candaceux.goodbarber.app/manage/settings/help/0/180/).

Beacons

These notifications are also triggered according to the behavior of users within a given range‚Äîthat of your Beacons, which are devices that send out Bluetooth wireless signals. 
Learn how to configure Beacons (https://candaceux.goodbarber.app/manage/settings/help/0/179/).

Also discover our video tutorial here (https://youtu.be/zSAbxW9AFZ0)

If you need help, feel free to contact our support team (https://candaceux.goodbarber.app/manage/settings/support/).

We hope this will be useful!

Hey friends,

Quick thing before we start: I‚Äôm hosting an in-person all-day
mastermind event in London on Friday 15th Aug, aimed at 6-fig+
entrepreneurs. If that‚Äôs you, more info here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/mvu2vm8x35t5hqowd0nf3irn9m0qqi3h5de26/25h2h9u3ogoelmb8/aHR0cHM6Ly9mb3Jtcy5nbGUvekpuVDRLejZyZWM1Y0RUeDk=
).

Anyway, it‚Äôs been a pretty rammed week - I‚Äôve been ‚Äúlocked-in‚Äù
(as they say) from like 8am to 11pm all day everyday working on
curriculum content for our $1k Challenge (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/mvu2vm8x35t5hqowd0nf3irn9m0qqi3h5de26/qvh8h8ud6v60elsg/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3RoZS0xay1jaGFsbGVuZ2UvP3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1sb2NraW4mdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWxpZmVub3Rlcw==
) starting in a few days. We‚Äôve got nearly 1,000 people from all
over the world joining, all aiming to build a business that makes
at least $1,000 in the next 6 weeks while building independent
income generation skills. Exciting and a little scary at the same
time.

In this week‚Äôs email, I wanted to share a realisation that I had
this week‚Ä¶ I‚Äôve had this realisation a few times in the past, but
it‚Äôs something I clearly always need to remind myself of.

You know how everyone says: ‚Äúconsistency is more important than
intensity‚Äù and ‚Äúit‚Äôs better to do a little everyday than a lot in
a single day‚Äù and all that stuff? That clearly applies to lots of
things in life - working out regularly is far more useful than
doing a mega workout once in a while. Doing 10 minutes of
stretching per day is more useful than doing 1h of stretching
once a week. Brushing your teeth everyday is‚Ä¶ you get the idea.

But when it comes to major creative projects, I‚Äôve often found
that the opposite is true: doing it in a burst of intensity is
more fun, and more generative, and leads to a better result, than
trying to chip away at it a few hours each week over several
months.

The most progress I made when working on Feel-Good Productivity
was 1 week when I was with my team in Wales, where I set myself
the challenge of drafting a whole chapter per day before I was
allowed to do the fun stuff the team were doing. It worked. The
second most progress I made was when I went on a writing retreat
type thing to Bali and spent all day everyday sitting in a cafe
locked-in, just working on the book. In those 2 weeks, I made
more progress than I did in 2 years of trying to chip away at it
1-2 hours per day.

When we launched the Part-Time YouTuber Academy (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/mvu2vm8x35t5hqowd0nf3irn9m0qqi3h5de26/g3hnhwumznzkg2u3/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWxpYWJkYWFsLmNvbS9wYXJ0LXRpbWUteW91dHViZXItYWNhZGVteS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWxvY2tpbl8yNyZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bGlmZW5vdGVz
) back in 2020, we built it from zero to launch within 2 weeks,
doing nothing else other than focusing on that. That product has
generated millions of dollars in revenue, and thousands of
successful students, and it was created in a ‚Äúsprint‚Äù rather than
through slow, stable consistency.

It‚Äôs been the same with this $1k Challenge (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/mvu2vm8x35t5hqowd0nf3irn9m0qqi3h5de26/qvh8h8ud6v60elsg/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3RoZS0xay1jaGFsbGVuZ2UvP3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1sb2NraW4mdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWxpZmVub3Rlcw==
) course content - I decided I wasn‚Äôt going to do anything else
this week, and just focused on that all day everyday for 7 days
in a row. And I‚Äôm pretty proud of the result.

There‚Äôs something about being fully immersed in a project, where
it‚Äôs the only thing you‚Äôre thinking about and dreaming about,
that (at least for me), seems to lead to interesting and novel
insights.

The issue of course, is that you have to clear the decks, and do
nothing else other than focus on the project. Even if you‚Äôre just
counting work time, and the project isn‚Äôt invading your evenings
and weekends, there‚Äôs often ‚Äúbusiness as usual‚Äù stuff that
happens - meetings, reports, keeping up with a consistent cadence
on publishing content, whatever it might be.

If your situation doesn‚Äôt give you the autonomy to be able to
clear the decks whenever you want to go deep on a project, then
of course, it‚Äôs sort of out of your hands‚Ä¶ but at least in my
case, I could always clear the decks whenever I want‚Ä¶ I could
always choose to cancel my meetings, not film any YouTube videos
that week, and lock-in on a new project - whether it‚Äôs a course,
or a book, or an app, or anything else really.

But for some reason‚Ä¶ I very rarely do. I always think: ‚ÄúYeah I‚Äôve
got this fun new project to work on that could really move the
needle for the business and for our students‚Ä¶‚Ä¶ but I‚Äôm sure THIS
TIME I can make it happen working on it 1h per day, while I
continue to do all the other things I‚Äôve got in my calendar as
well‚Äù.

And then weeks or months pass, I haven‚Äôt made much progress with
the new thing, because I‚Äôm on the hamster wheel of keeping all
the existing things going.

My friend and former team member, Tintin, mentioned this sort of
thing casually in his newsletter one time a few weeks ago. It was
something like: ‚ÄúYou can only do one thing at a time. If you‚Äôve
got limited resources, it‚Äôs REALLY HARD to build (for example) an
online course WHILE keeping up your 1-2 videos a week upload
schedule on YouTube. If you want to make significant progress in
your business, you have to be okay with sacrificing the video
consistency for the sake of the new product‚Äù.

It‚Äôs the sacrifice that makes this hard. The short-term stuff of
‚Äúbut the content engine needs to keep ticking, we‚Äôve got sponsor
deadlines coming up, if I take a break from YouTube the channel
will die forever‚Ä¶‚Äù - all that takes away from the important (and
generally, more fun) aspects of working deeply on a new project
to get it off the ground.

Actually, I see this exact same pattern with loads of aspiring
creators and entrepreneurs I chat to. They‚Äôre trying to juggle
their day job, maybe some side content creation, learning new
skills, keeping up with social media, and then on top of all
that, they want to launch their first business or YouTube channel
or whatever. But here‚Äôs the thing - they imagine they can somehow
fit it all in without sacrificing anything else. Like they‚Äôll
just squeeze in 30 minutes of building their business between
their existing commitments, and somehow that‚Äôll be enough to get
something meaningful off the ground.

The maths just doesn‚Äôt work though. There are literally only so
many hours in the week, and most of us are already overdrawn on
our time and energy. If you‚Äôre already feeling stretched with
your current commitments, adding ‚Äúbuild a business from scratch‚Äù
to the mix isn‚Äôt going to work by just doing it in tiny
increments. And it‚Äôs not just about time either - it‚Äôs about
headspace. Getting something new off the ground requires this
weird kind of mental bandwidth where you‚Äôre constantly thinking
about the problem, having random insights in the shower, making
connections between different ideas. You can‚Äôt really get into
that flow state if you‚Äôre context-switching between your new
project and 15 other things every day.

So I reckon there‚Äôs a strong case for a sprint-based approach to
making new stuff happen. If you‚Äôre trying to launch your first
business, maybe block out a whole weekend where you‚Äôve got no
social plans, no other commitments, and you just lock-in and make
some proper progress. Clear the mental space as well as the
calendar.

Same thing if you‚Äôre learning a new skill that could level up
your career, or trying to build your first online course, or
whatever. Instead of spreading it out over 6 months doing 20
minutes here and there, see if you can carve out a week or two
where that becomes your main thing.

I get that not everyone has the flexibility to just cancel
everything and go into hermit mode whenever they want. But even
if you can‚Äôt do it as often as you‚Äôd like, doing it occasionally
- maybe once a quarter? Once every 6 months? - could be way more
effective than the slow-and-steady approach that everyone talks
about.

Something to think about anyway.

Have a great week!

Ali xx

When it comes to writing, a lot of people think, ‚ÄúOh wow, I can

alert - it doesn‚Äôt quite work like that.

The way I see it, Claude (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/mvu2vm8x35t5hqowd0nf3irn9m0qqi3h5de26/9qhzhdud2x2l47bz/aHR0cDovL2NsYXUuZGUvbGlmZW5vdGVz

times. But instead of expecting it to nail things perfectly in
one go, the real value in writing with Claude comes from having a
back-and-forth conversation - where it helps you think outside
the box and develop your ideas further.

So previously, writing my LifeNotes issues used to take me about
2 hours, but now, thanks to Claude, I‚Äôve cut that down to about
30 minutes. Throughout the week, I‚Äôll note down my ideas and by
the time I sit down to write properly, I‚Äôve already got a bank of
useful material ready to go.

My writing process is also incredibly efficient because I always
use a dedicated Claude (

examples of past issues and stuff I‚Äôve written before, as the
more information you give Claude, the better its responses will
be and the more easily it adapts to your tone and style of voice.

Beyond writing, I use Claude (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/mvu2vm8x35t5hqowd0nf3irn9m0qqi3h5de26/9qhzhdud2x2l47bz/aHR0cDovL2NsYXUuZGUvbGlmZW5vdGVz
) for all sorts of other things - idea generation, data analysis,

Hey Candace,

¬†

I seen you‚Äôve been reading my emails for a while now‚Ä¶

¬†

(Thank you ‚Äî it means more than you know.)

¬†

And I have a feeling your heart‚Äôs been pulling you toward something deeper.

Something more meaningful.

Something that looks a lot like‚Ä¶ becoming a coach.

¬†

But maybe you‚Äôre still unsure. Maybe you're still asking:

¬†

‚ÄúCan I really do this?‚Äù

‚ÄúIs now the right time?‚Äù

‚ÄúWill it actually make a difference ‚Äî in my life and in others?‚Äù

¬†

Here‚Äôs what I want you to know:

¬†

If you feel called to help people‚Ä¶

If you want to live with more purpose‚Ä¶

Hey Candace,

Quick thing before we start, I mentioned CreatorGrid in a
previous email (the platform that we‚Äôre building to help creators
grow and monetise) and I just wanted to let you know that we‚Äôve
also opened up a limited number of Creator-in-Residence
opportunities as part of this venture. If you‚Äôre a creator and
interested in applying, you can do so here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/wvugd3nzo9bghkxew2wf7hn62gkxxs8h4lw6v/vqh3hmuoevee67iw/aHR0cHM6Ly9nby5zcGFya2xlLnNvL2NuLzI5
).

Anyway, hope you‚Äôve had a great week so far üôå

I was away again last week and so filming has continued to take a
bit of a hit this month but hoping to be back in the studio later
this week. But I wanted to use this email to talk about something
that‚Äôs been on my mind more and more recently given these filming
struggles and that‚Äôs the idea of the creation-to-consumption
ratio.

This is basically the number of hours you‚Äôve spent consuming
stuff that‚Äôs been created by other people in the last 7 days,
divided by the number of hours you‚Äôve spent creating something
yourself. And ideally, you want to be spending at least as many
hours creating as you do consuming, or even better, spending more
time creating than consuming.

Why? Because most people who want to start a YouTube channel
don‚Äôt have a clear idea of what they actually want to post or
talk about because they haven‚Äôt created enough stuff yet. They‚Äôve
spent years - or sometimes decades - consuming content, but very
little time actually making things themselves.

And it‚Äôs in this sort of messy, imperfect process of making stuff
that you essentially figure out everything that makes your
channel uniquely yours - so your niche, filming style, editing
process, thumbnail aesthetic, and all that super important stuff
when it comes to YouTube.

You‚Äôll also start to notice patterns like ‚Äúhuh, I really enjoy
making tutorial videos but I absolutely hate doing vlogs‚Äù or ‚ÄúI
love the scriptwriting phase but I find editing a slog‚Äù or ‚ÄúI get
way more excited talking about personal finance than I do about
productivity‚Äù.

Once you figure out what energises you rather than drains you,
staying consistent on YouTube becomes so much easier. You‚Äôre no
longer grinding your way through content you hate making - you‚Äôre
leaning into what you naturally enjoy, which means you‚Äôll
actually want to keep showing up.

Paul Graham, the founder of Y Combinator, puts it perfectly in
his essay How to Do What You Love:

‚ÄúAlways produce‚Äù is also a heuristic for finding the work you
love. If you subject yourself to that constraint, it will
automatically push you away from things you think you‚Äôre supposed
to work on, toward things you actually like.

And Steven Spielberg is a fantastic example of this - he didn‚Äôt
start out with a grand master plan to break into Hollywood as
this insanely good director. He was just a kid messing around
with his dad‚Äôs camcorder, making random short films with his
friends. But through that constant creation, he figured out what
he loved, got better at his craft, and eventually turned that
into a career.

The same principle applies with YouTube (or any creative
endeavour really). You don‚Äôt need to have it all figured out
before you start, you just need to create stuff and let the
process reveal what works for you.

So if you‚Äôre feeling a bit stuck with YouTube, my challenge for
you this week is to try and shift your creation-to-consumption
ratio.

Let‚Äôs say you spent 10 hours consuming content last week -
watching YouTube, scrolling on TikTok or Instagram, and reading
articles. That means you‚Äôd want to aim for at least 10 hours of
creating this week, whether that‚Äôs filming, writing scripts,
editing, or designing thumbnails, whatever the thing may be.

But if that feels overwhelming, just aim to create for 1-2 hours
this week. The specific numbers matter way less than the actual
habit of making creation a part of your routine, and even if what
you create isn‚Äôt perfect or never gets published, the act of
making will give you more clarity than any amount of planning or
consuming ever could.

Hope today‚Äôs email was useful and if you start tracking your
creation-to-consumption ratio, hit reply and let me know.

See you next week,

Ali xx

P.S üëÄ

I know some of you reading this might be thinking, ‚Äúokay Ali,
that all sounds great in theory but I‚Äôve literally never made a
video before - I don‚Äôt even know where to start.‚Äù And it that‚Äôs
you, I totally get it - the gap between ‚ÄúI should create more‚Äù
and actually hitting publish on your first video can feel huge.

column7: Stuck on self-doubt? Try this Candace...
column9:
We all struggle with doubt.

¬†

It‚Äôs your mind's way of protecting you from ‚Äúscary‚Äù change it thinks might hurt you.

¬†

Even change YOU WANT.

¬†

So if you don‚Äôt keep a close eye on this‚Ä¶

¬†

Your doubt can become like a shadow over a tree, stopping you from growing and reaching new heights.

¬†

Holding you back from your true potential.

¬†

I‚Äôve seen it so many times before‚Ä¶

¬†

And I don‚Äôt want that to be you, Candace.

That‚Äôs why I want to share Val‚Äôs story‚Ä¶

¬†

She was sitting where you are, just a few months ago.

¬†

She‚Äôd wanted to be a coach for years.

But she kept putting it off - telling herself she wasn‚Äôt ready.

¬†

Part of that came from what she believed about ‚Äúsuccess‚Äù.

¬†

She thought that meant having a degree, and coaching didn‚Äôt quite fit that picture.

¬†

So she put her dream on hold‚Ä¶

¬†

‚ÄúSomeday‚Äù she‚Äôd do it.

¬†

But that day never came until she stopped doubting herself.

¬†

And made a decision to put her purpose first.

¬†

Even though she wasn't quite ‚Äúready yet‚Äù - she knew she couldn‚Äôt stay as she was any longer.

And once Val said ‚Äúyes‚Äù to joining our school‚Ä¶

¬†

She didn‚Äôt just learn how to coach - she felt her whole life crack open.

¬†

‚úÖ She finally became her most authentic self.

¬†

‚úÖ She reconnected with her purpose.

¬†

‚úÖ And she gave herself permission to take up space as the powerful, heart-led woman she‚Äôd always been.

¬†

Today, Val helps other high-achieving women who are struggling behind their success.

¬†

Showing them how to ‚Äúcome home‚Äù to themselves, trust their own voice, and live a life that feels more aligned with their true purpose.

All this is to say‚Ä¶

¬†

Val didn‚Äôt feel ‚Äúready‚Äù when she enrolled in my school ( https://pages.jayshettycoaching.com/rewarding-career-video-bau-e/?el=RNC-email-self-doubt-169-2&utm_campaign_name=JSCS%3A+Prospects+Week+169-2&utm_content_name=Stuck+on+self-doubt%3F+Try+this+Name...&utm_medium_name=email_action&utm_source_name=customer.io ) and started training to become a coach.

¬†

But she let it be the turning point she needed.

¬†

And now she‚Äôs creating an incredible impact, doing something she loves every day.

¬†

If you‚Äôve been holding yourself back too, Candace‚Ä¶

¬†

This is your moment to turn the corner:

¬†

community in East Texas, I felt as if I had entered a fairy village. One of the
tiny homes was pink with white polka dots. Another was surrounded by towering
sunflowers. Nine dogs roamed freely.

Eleven women, most of them single, live there. They tend the grounds themselves,
planting gardens and laying pipe. They‚Äôre trying to create what so many people
seem to want in their later years: privacy and autonomy, caring and mutual
support, friendship and laughs.

I recently visited the Bird‚Äôs Nest to learn about the community these women have
made
[https://nl.nytimes.com/f/newsletter/slUH_d6VcySoY5-DTNkOTA~~/AAAAARA~/Z6PmmAuDJtAFSR_TLSw-0a5t3SPyAzU2dvQDWB1zK_ZstgVxoH5z2dUnssHNlC5AfLB-JZCQ4UAeFHmsc57UQMy5g36bCooh2tnirWeJubdgeUq5ZirzE091t87sQpklCDATL80lOVlWVFTJnetKAWE-cFNG6VmZu9xoem07pF61VwnMH8e9EVpgorx6h6r2ejo5ey1nNJ_Js9swGx-tOg7YpBwy7o3ZXeBSgB81nlFLoeG-KqGoLMisBPCx2yOe60QKBQacvJHt0H4db54DEWKkM7LSHbBhWc-oXfxhkin19quV7MWV_lLRFReywl9Vs8pNEZULmtsxkYyKfFnpMTzctgOZubobn-EkEdVF4LMlo6Nv5FYTRB0QW81p3MO7I9thUnmD7TNfPlhSWOKBug~~] 
and the solutions it offers for the problems of loneliness and affordability so
many of us wish we could creatively avoid. Here‚Äôs what I found.

AN UNCLUTTERED LIFE
A woman stands in front of a polka dot house with two dogs. [https://static01.nyt.com/images/2025/08/08/multimedia/08themorning-nl-LEAD5-hwmj/08themorning-nl-LEAD5-hwmj-jumbo.jpg]
Robyn Yerian, founder of The Bird‚Äôs Nest.Shelby Tauber for The New York Times
When Robyn Yerian founded The Bird‚Äôs Nest back in 2022, affordability was her
main concern. Yerian ‚Äî divorced, mother of two, now 70 years old ‚Äî was ‚Äúout of
options,‚Äù she told me. She lived and worked in Dallas and couldn‚Äôt retire
comfortably on what she had.

Her problem was a common one. According to the AARP, 64 percent of single,
working American women ages 50 to 64 have less than $50,000 in retirement
savings. (That‚Äôs true for around 50 percent of men.)

So Yerian cashed out her 401(k) and bought a cheap plot of land on a remote
stretch of prairie. She charges others just $450 a month in rent. The women of
The Bird‚Äôs Nest told me they were drawn there in part by that affordability.
They were at the end of their working lives and didn‚Äôt want to live with family.
The tiny-house lifestyle also appealed: A 300-square-foot home has a small
footprint, it‚Äôs easy to clean and it can be customized.

But what the women really liked about The Bird‚Äôs Nest, they said, was Yerian.
Cheerful, generous and energetic, she is an excellent baker, skilled with power
tools and concerned about every member‚Äôs day-to-day happiness. Her vision, which
has evolved over time, is now one of ‚Äúwomen empowering women.‚Äù She sees it as a
retirement destination where women can relax with uninhibited ease. As one of
the members joked, she has ‚Äúunintentionally created an intentional community.‚Äù

FAST FRIENDS
Women working on mosaics, seen from above. [https://static01.nyt.com/images/2025/08/04/multimedia/08themorning-nl-LEAD6/08themorning-nl-LEAD6-jumbo.jpg]
Working on mosaics to use as address numbers.Shelby Tauber for The New York
TimesThe women of The Bird‚Äôs Nest moved from Illinois, Tennessee and Arizona,
among other places. They are straight and gay. Republican, Democrat and
independent. Religious and agnostic. They disagree, sometimes passionately, over
politics. But long lives have given them a similar perspective. ‚ÄúThere‚Äôs no
sense in arguing over what you can‚Äôt change,‚Äù one member told me. The first rule
of the community ‚Äî unofficially, because Yerian doesn‚Äôt like rules ‚Äî is ‚Äúno
drama.‚Äù

My visit there made me think about friendship. I have long had the fantasy of
retiring together with my friends from college, buying a big house and chipping
in for accessibility ramps as needed. And I know many other people with a
similar dream. But the truth is that friends in established groups don‚Äôt get
ready to retire at the same time. They are differently tied down to careers,
partners, neighborhoods, kids. They have different levels of financial need.

It‚Äôs far better to think about how you want to live in your last chapter, and
how much you can afford. And then, as Yerian did, recruit other people to join
you. Just as we made friends in earlier chapters of our lives ‚Äî high school,
college, the workplace, parenthood ‚Äî we can make new ones for this stage. All
the women at The Bird‚Äôs Nest would agree. Yerian now says she has ‚Äúinstant
friends, best friends at 65. I never saw these people before in my life, and now
I can‚Äôt imagine them not being here every day.‚Äù
