column7: üîã Productivity Advice I Need To Tell Myself
column9:
Hey Candace,

Hope you had a fantastic weekend üôå

I know this isn‚Äôt CreatorNotes (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/mvu2vm8x35t5hq0w5ozhmhr899lqqs3/48hvh7umpep0nvcq/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2NyZWF0b3Itbm90ZXM=
) (my newsletter for creators) but I wanted to use today‚Äôs email
to talk about filming - or more specifically - my recent lack of
filming and the productivity lessons I've been forced to
remember...again üò¨.

Over the last couple of months, I‚Äôve found it hard to get into a
rhythm with filming and we've missed our content output targets.
Whether it be YouTube videos or Instagram Reels, I‚Äôve just been
struggling with getting over the traditional blockers when it
comes to creativity or productivity.

And I‚Äôve tried various fixes like waking up earlier, changing up
my routine, trying to force my way through the creative block
just to get it done. But the truth is, that hasn‚Äôt worked. Not
sustainably, anyway.

It was only talking with some of my team when they were here in
Hong Kong last month that I realised that maybe the issue isn‚Äôt
one of discipline or willpower. Maybe the issue was more to do
with my energy.

And over the next few weeks, it was increasingly obvious that
that was probably true. That week when everyone was here (and the
weeks since then, when new team members have started to work with
me in-person) have been some of the most productive parts of the
year. Suddenly, the work doesn‚Äôt feel like a lonely grind, it
feels like a team effort and somehow that same filming feels
easier and...more energising.

This shouldn't be a surprise and to be honest, I perhaps
should‚Äôve recognised it earlier. After all, in Feel-Good
Productivity (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/mvu2vm8x35t5hq0w5ozhmhr899lqqs3/wnh2h6uqkpkr37tl/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2ZlZWwtZ29vZC1wcm9kdWN0aXZpdHkv
), I talk about how the easiest way to stay consistent is to make
hard things more enjoyable and if something energises me, I‚Äôm far
more likely to enjoy it and therefore get it done, even if it‚Äôs
challenging, so I know how important that energy piece can be for
personal productivity.

And if you‚Äôve read the book, you‚Äôll know that there are three
core ways to think about this - Play, Power and People.

Play is really about how you can add a sense of fun and novelty
to your work; Power comes from the meaning that you attach to
tasks and then People is really the area that I realised I‚Äôd been
missing - that sense of companionship and accountability.

And I know I‚Äôll still face resistance. Some days, I‚Äôll do
everything except the one thing I‚Äôm supposed to do (much to my
team‚Äôs frustration üòÖ) but when I take a beat and ask myself, ‚ÄúHow
could I make this even a little bit more enjoyable?‚Äù the answer
is usually there. A small tweak in environment, mindset, or
support can get the wheels turning and it's certainly done that
for me over recent weeks by putting more emphasis on that people
component.

So here‚Äôs something to try: take one task you‚Äôve been avoiding,
something you keep bumping down your to-do list, and ask
yourself:

* How could I make this 10% more fun?
* How could I connect this to something meaningful?
* How could I work with someone to make this more energising?

I hope this serves as a useful reminder that getting things done
isn‚Äôt just about discipline or powering your way through a task
list and these prompts are helpful in allowing you to think about
ways to get through creative or productivity obstacles in your
own life.

Have a great week and we'll speak again next Monday :)

Ali xx

P.S - if you‚Äôre like me and it‚Äôs the accountability piece that
you find yourself struggling with, then you might want to check
out LifeOS Pro (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/mvu2vm8x35t5hq0w5ozhmhr899lqqs3/reh8h9um3r3qeza6/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWVuZXJneV8yOCZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9cHJvZHVjdGl2ZW5vdGVz

   .

More news is below. But first, we have a Silicon Valley vibe check.

A worker on a crane removes the letters of a ‚ÄúTwitter‚Äù sign from the side of a building.  [https://static01.nyt.com/images/2025/08/04/multimedia/04themorning-nl-lede-khqc/04themorning-nl-lede-khqc-jumbo-v3.jpg]
A Twitter sign being removed in San Francisco in 2023.Jim Wilson/The New York
TimesSYSTEM UPGRADE
Author Headshot
[https://static01.nyt.com/images/2025/03/01/reader-center/author-adam-b-kushner/author-adam-b-kushner-blogSmallThumb.png]
[https://nl.nytimes.com/f/newsletter/w47lbKHoJ6bDD4zjWbgkpQ~~/AAAAARA~/mGpW9xQEUWbgSqhh1h1rJ38L_ztECUd54Dj8G8DuyhaK65WKBqOHA3ZMNzTAfmth3wgXHafFE_svphcwroJhDqXKy-Dtuqc9Z7zbi2lALidcL5x5ySq8QZAQjtV-1Q_WfZzvXPreB9IBo2xETyCx1OJxZNUbilWt2i_TOPfKV5dMDp7rZsMXbQCWW4KvY6G20UJbtVytzC8AS_yZtRHbhrOwtnDbn_5wpgfZgoYvvE8SydpOZbBSgWJJgpDnyF25Lt25grgFKFNRDnil-UBINfLqzRPs6aGuftN--ss8l89IHMpGwDuGsklqQQHFqTnS0TVYHXopV3LGRxxHIO5rvg~~]
By Adam B. Kushner
[https://nl.nytimes.com/f/newsletter/w47lbKHoJ6bDD4zjWbgkpQ~~/AAAAARA~/mGpW9xQEUWbgSqhh1h1rJ38L_ztECUd54Dj8G8DuyhaK65WKBqOHA3ZMNzTAfmth3wgXHafFE_svphcwroJhDqXKy-Dtuqc9Z7zbi2lALidcL5x5ySq8QZAQjtV-1Q_WfZzvXPreB9IBo2xETyCx1OJxZNUbilWt2i_TOPfKV5dMDp7rZsMXbQCWW4KvY6G20UJbtVytzC8AS_yZtRHbhrOwtnDbn_5wpgfZgoYvvE8SydpOZbBSgWJJgpDnyF25Lt25grgFKFNRDnil-UBINfLqzRPs6aGuftN--ss8l89IHMpGwDuGsklqQQHFqTnS0TVYHXopV3LGRxxHIO5rvg~~]

I‚Äôm the editor of this newsletter.

Silicon Valley has transformed. No surprise there ‚Äî change is its business,
after all. But just as artificial intelligence will upend the economy, it has
already upended the culture of the place that makes it.

America‚Äôs tech corridor holds immense influence over our future. So it‚Äôs worth
understanding life there ‚Äî and the people who power it. Today‚Äôs newsletter is
about the new vibe in Silicon Valley. That‚Äôs the focus of several stories our
tech journalists have recently reported from the world‚Äôs tech capital.

‚ÄòSHUT UP AND GRIND‚Äô
Silicon Valley behemoths like Google, Apple and Facebook became famous a
generation ago for pitching great lifestyle jobs: Forget the cubicles and
neckties of the old economy. Come enjoy free sushi and workout classes; take
breaks for Ping-Pong. Let‚Äôs change the world!

Then, around 2022, they decided they had become bloated. Meta eliminated a third
of its work force. Elon Musk bought Twitter and fired three-quarters of its
staff.

New focus. The job cuts weren‚Äôt just about economics. They were also about
priorities. Over the years, leaders felt progressive politics had overtaken the
workplace. Now companies began to nix ‚Äúmoderators, marketers, media handlers and
all things associated with diversity and inclusion,‚Äù writes my colleague Mike
Isaac, who chronicles this seismic realignment
[https://nl.nytimes.com/f/newsletter/sgvS9EpHxO9fvPRUAOl2Vw~~/AAAAARA~/6AyjphX5riTHNbS-0q_zB35z5DuDuvtDWa0O0rKPCGMrNNOmifeRMa0eoCr8gfiqwewNeROk1pMSSZkbHlH49M59UkKNmQX6ZF3eRYCzk34ps-h_djjV6AkBLR7mY-rZeyp8dmAwZPvGnbi3AfhePlSknljo0fvb64-ekGMzPM1RriIU8GnzDwnuQ-lNdQnMYpmHtPfeUqbgfr3AeLwd7pJS21fojOchL13VlVKlzEwlTmAXzX4Syl3Rr4l4n0VZrFVzOR71CdaFIhWJrc_asmEPo0Oje7clq9ztHAhvEpYmde-1p2ppkG8EIJq0Dgn5ux99C3k-gUlcqH5WIqJ29vXHYkk6m2IblNy_amO5ID4Q5VMR2m3LUFsoU7gAO_Uf]
. ‚ÄúHeaven help those with a humanities degree.‚Äù

Masters of war. The new priorities include something that tech‚Äôs early
do-gooders had forsworn: digital armaments. As Sheera Frenkel reports, Meta,
Google and OpenAI once banned the use of artificial intelligence in weapons.
Today, OpenAI makes anti-drone tech
[https://nl.nytimes.com/f/newsletter/zOqSXc5qyuijSXnKMmHgtA~~/AAAAARA~/N_gbRtq6PAaFPxB_MI9A5FA0ZR3C6jvQWJpQpgN75qu3d7gUP-qxxewInM0TytMeWYcFGkVW_OuaxwpodO5r7fCA0L0Uv1qkF2qIU3JZi_h5L93V7U8swHfHxQYd4CZF9mucxFV0kXI3yDHpBPiTXtP4rZ5lad39VSvXEJ0_XVZObQrciysqtjFdDd5tPtYcO6Ja9NbLfWCKSz7pSush6Od6R3h0_wqsoys9F-QyrXMReKhZhkZobivicIYzQEJRQR0HZhWi_gZtO1goTt4aOrbFv_fSrlG9Ryfy8SzUoU9k11ca7cOF8MAJQdF_ianGbHG7N_LLU7jrtZ_E3KDxXc9IjfUEfpdh62ZwwRxnokEyTnuu31sY1G8EtKxvM9KG]
, and Meta makes virtual reality glasses to train soldiers. One start-up sells
drones fitted with A.I.-guided cruise missiles.

Fervid toil. Corporate dogma has changed. Now executives want hard skills, not
soft ones. They‚Äôre not focused on consumer payment and photo-sharing apps;
they‚Äôre building neural networks, ordering people back to the office and
censoring employee debate.

‚ÄúIt‚Äôs the shut up and grind era,‚Äù writes Kate Conger, who has a great dispatch

column7: ‚ú® You‚Äôre in! Here‚Äôs your first dose of wisdom.
column9:
Hi there,

Thank you for choosing Weekly Wisdom.

You‚Äôre joining a community of over 650k readers. I‚Äôm so happy you‚Äôre here.

You might know me from my #1 podcast, ‚Äú[On Purpose.](https://link.mail.beehiiv.com/ss/c/u001.FrWGzCABiYTGGxh_nSeWlMP89grG-TrA30WLca9WgcNTR9sIxKugTEyUioDBDv4iOb7oVHZGqoZNYy8tiiITkg/4jk/wiVqYC9vQ46v2wBSJsIU5Q/t0/h001.5Rfwdu4f1aZiUjPRDRLqhb-X_ix-HtoTIL9sjPSTfWk

I‚Äôm also a _New York Times_ bestselling author and personal development coach, forever curious about the well-being best practices that make our lives more purposeful.

I‚Äôve been writing this newsletter every week since December 2020. I pick topics based on the questions readers like you send me.

I write to:

* **Help you improve your everyday life**

* **Open your mind and expand your soul.**

* **Give you a sense of hope.**

Each week, I answer a new question that could be relevant, useful, and healing to all 650,000 of my readers.

To get started, dive into one of a recent popular Weekly Wisdom‚Äî[my answer to a reader who said, ‚ÄúI‚Äôm afraid I‚Äôm drifting apart from the people closest to me, but I don‚Äôt know what to do.‚Äù](https://link.mail.beehiiv.com/ss/c/u001.lvbdQEA5OL3DTa-yJ8ntSRJIbR0dFmSao3AF9wGuL7NmRrtb4c-DkeeC4SBxOAEYp7spndCWqRbSqqtUSh38Ak2dnF89D_mc4WhCNn5wjZ4bjXhw-URhAqY4fCcE6aSjODhkKEfhfjWHrAIxBPf3cvYwjICvMYwVwimrmZAmjcz6wdpFQ9zqXZh2gGHU67D8_VdC3FiPdSrm3ml_t590DDHCKSZiMH6tCKLnI_rPNRJR6_1lJ02hhX-qyfokntUDb03zQZNPt8d_O5R5nZbpjuf-2ZEFbSPYhik-0jZIfds/4jk/wiVqYC9vQ46v2wBSJsIU5Q/t1/h001.oNpWQjy7bKlw1CAeefw8OWM5HWm5jW17_3QpHPl2ToI

As a new subscriber, here‚Äôs what you can expect:

* **Consistency:** Every Thursday, I‚Äôll be in your inbox, no matter what. I haven‚Äôt missed an issue in the four years I‚Äôve been writing this newsletter.

* **Special Offers and Workshops:** This doesn‚Äôt happen often, but every now and then, my team will create a free, limited-time-only workshop. Be the first to know about my special offers and events before the general public is notified.

**Let‚Äôs ensure we stay connected‚Äîhere‚Äôs how to ensure Weekly Wisdom lands directly in your inbox.**

**If you use Apple Mail:**

Tap on my email address at the top of this message‚Äîright next to the ‚ÄúFrom‚Äù field. Then choose ‚ÄúAdd to Contacts‚Äù or ‚ÄúAdd to VIPs.‚Äù

**If you use Gmail:**

On your computer, go to your main inbox and drag this email to the ‚ÄúPrimary‚Äù tab.

On your phone, tap the three dots in the top right corner of this message, then choose ‚ÄúMove To‚Äù and select ‚ÄúPrimary.‚Äù

**If you use Outlook:**

Click the banner at the top that says ‚ÄúClick here to download pictures.‚Äù Then, select ‚ÄúAdd Sender to Safe Senders list.‚Äù


Before I sign off, I want to thank you again for being here.

You are the reason this community of readers is so incredible.

**With gratitude,**

Jay Shetty

**P.S. While you‚Äôre here, want to go one step further with me?**


When I saw how many people were joining Weekly Wisdom, I knew I wanted to do something special‚Ä¶

Not just any old welcome email‚Ä¶

But _a __**real opportunity for accelerated growth**_ that our new subscribers could take full advantage of immediately.

So I built the most valuable offer I‚Äôve ever put together for this community‚Ä¶

It‚Äôs called [Jay Shetty‚Äôs Ultimate Life Upgrade Collection.](https://link.mail.beehiiv.com/ss/c/u001.qGCi09IsbUHEcx-VdN0bHE7CzKyT9J0Q8pVlQUAXJ_T05sh1xSWyJjx2r_bej5jQ2slMwfvTvqxMX7xivnaaKvJqIYesUa-aOhzcexCpANo/4jk/wiVqYC9vQ46v2wBSJsIU5Q/t2/h001.UNM19Ha7RBrjb-hoj16tnOiDMrbwQ1DJd2X406ykYsE

It includes six of my most powerful mini-courses to upgrade your life in the areas you care about most:¬†

**Purpose, Love, Wellness, Mindset, Manifestation, and Meditation.¬†**

_**Plus**_, you‚Äôll get a **live group coaching session** with one of my top growth coaches‚Äîyour chance to gain clarity, motivation, and real next steps toward your goals.

Normally, this bundle is valued at $550. But as a welcome gift and thank you for being a new Weekly Wisdom reader, you can get access to _everything_ for just __**$**____**99**____**.**__

**I‚Äôve never offered this much value in one place for a price like this. Ever.**

This limited-time offer is only available for the next few days, so if it feels like the right next step, [I invite you to check it out right now.](https://link.mail.beehiiv.com/ss/c/u001.qGCi09IsbUHEcx-VdN0bHE7CzKyT9J0Q8pVlQUAXJ_T05sh1xSWyJjx2r_bej5jQ2slMwfvTvqxMX7xivnaaKvJqIYesUa-aOhzcexCpANo/4jk/wiVqYC9vQ46v2wBSJsIU5Q/t3/h001.gbBubmX-5m0Wcqud8hecgn2ssiIwlnQbFQuofnlJjKw

column7: You should get to know this headhunter
üëâ This One Simple Habit Doubled My Productivity
column9:
Hey Candace,

Quick thing before we start - we‚Äôre running a special limited
time offer on our flagship YouTube programme, the Part-Time
YouTuber Academy just for one week. If you‚Äôre a creator looking
to start, grow or scale your channel or business, you can sign up
to hear about the offer by clicking here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/wvugd3nzo9bghkvzzrra7hnvz9zxxi8/3ohqr3omidu3rn3v6rfp/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3BhcnQtdGltZS15b3V0dWJlci1hY2FkZW15LW1heS0yMDI1LXRoYW5rLXlvdS8=
) üëÄ

Anyway, let's move to today's email and I want to talk about the
simple but powerful shift that I think is at the heart of what
really makes a day productive and that's moving from being
reactive to proactive.

This might sound simple but let me explain.

When you‚Äôre in reactive mode, you‚Äôre basically immediately
responding to everything that comes your way‚ÄîSlack messages,
emails, requests from your boss or manager. And don‚Äôt get me
wrong, there are some jobs out there that are entirely
reactive‚Äîlike air traffic control officers, for example. When
you‚Äôre guiding planes through the sky in real time, reacting
quickly is your job. ‚úàÔ∏è

But for most of us knowledge workers, real progress comes from
being proactive about how we spend our time and what we choose to
work on. üìÜ

In theory, we could all spend our time only reacting to what‚Äôs
happening, but you probably wouldn‚Äôt get much work done‚Äîor at
least, nothing truly valuable. So you need to flip the switch
from reactive mode to proactive mode, and one of the best ways
I‚Äôve found to do that is by simply tracking how much focus time
I‚Äôm actually stacking up each day.

Because if the only change you made was to start consistently
tracking your Focus Minutes, you‚Äôd (probably) double your
productivity ‚è∞

Just to give you my own experience with this, I use a couple of
apps that integrate across my devices and when I‚Äôm on my laptop,
I always see this little focus timer ticking away in the toolbar
at the top of my screen.

But if I‚Äôm working without the timer running‚Äîand it‚Äôs not
incrementing for every second that I‚Äôm actually focusing on the
task‚ÄîI get distracted a lot more easily. I get up to make a tea,
or a coffee, go to the toilet, pick up my guitar and start
singing, go to the toilet again‚Ä¶I think you get the picture. üòÇ

So without a doubt, my timer helps me get way more meaningful
work done.

If your next question then is, ‚ÄúBut Ali, how much focus time
should I aim for each day?‚Äù‚Äîthe answer‚Äôs pretty clear in this
case too.

When you look at the habits of super high-performing people, they
tend to land somewhere between 3 and 5 hours of focused work per
day. That‚Äôs pretty much the upper limit for deep, proactive work.

For some people, 3 hours is absolutely nothing. But others are
like, ‚ÄúHoly hell‚ÄîI can barely manage 30 minutes. How am I
supposed to do three hours?!‚Äù ü§Ø

So for anyone reading this who relates to that, my advice is to
just start with a single hour. Because that‚Äôs already a massive
win. And if you can steadily build up your Focus Minutes over
time, you‚Äôll end up being way more productive and make faster
progress toward the goals you actually care about.

This is exactly what I tell my students in LifeOS (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/wvugd3nzo9bghkvzzrra7hnvz9zxxi8/qvh8h8udv0dqg0hg/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXJlYWN0aXZlXzEyJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1wcm9kdWN0aXZlbm90ZXM=
) where we explore this idea in more detail - you can get more
information here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/wvugd3nzo9bghkvzzrra7hnvz9zxxi8/qvh8h8udv0dqg0hg/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXJlYWN0aXZlXzEyJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1wcm9kdWN0aXZlbm90ZXM=
).

Thanks, as always, for tuning in, and I‚Äôll see you next week! üòä

Ali xx

Hi Candace Grant,

We're introducing new features to enhance Kaggle and Google Colabintegration, along with other updates. Whether you're training models,exploring data, or competing, you can now leverage Colab within the Kaggleenvironment more easily and access additional GPU resources as a Colab Prouser to accelerate your work.





Here's what's new:


Additional Kaggle GPU with Colab Pro: For a limited time, Kagglers can getadditional GPU hours if they subscribe to Colab Pro.
Connect Colab and VS Code to Kaggle Jupyter Servers: You can now connectyour preferred notebook editor directly to Kaggle's powerful JupyterServers, hence leveraging Kaggle's hardware (GPUs, TPUs) and optimizedfilesystems (datasets, models) in your workflows.
Import Notebooks to Kaggle: You can now easily import your notebooks intoKaggle from Colab, GitHub, external URLs or local files. Streamline yourworkflow and get started faster.
Easily sync Colab notebooks: You can now instantly pull and sync notebooksimported from Colab and submit them to the Kaggle competition. We've alsointroduced a feature to import multiple notebooks from Colab at once.


We can't wait to see what you build with these updates. Try them out andlet us know what you think.

Happy Kaggling!

The Kaggle Team



Kaggle, Inc 1600 Amphitheatre Pkwy Mountain View, CA 94043

# Q: What does it mean to stay humble?

The winningest coach in NBA history, Gregg Popovich, retired in May. [The San Antonio Spurs won a whopping 5 NBA championships under his leadership](https://www.nba.com/news/spurs-unveil-gregg-popovich-banner). He‚Äôs arguably got a lot to gloat about.

But there‚Äôs a story I read about in The [Athletic](https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/6168664/2025/05/02/gregg-popovich-retirement-spurs-nba-leadership-legacy/) that highlights something truly remarkable about Coach Pop (Popovich‚Äôs nickname).

According to Golden State Warriors coach Steve Kerr, every time Coach Pop pours a drink for the people around his table, nobody is allowed to sip until he makes a toast. And the toast is the same every single time.

_‚ÄúHere‚Äôs to Tim Duncan.‚Äù_

Now, if you don‚Äôt know, [Tim Duncan](https://www.nba.com/stats/player/1495/career) is the basketball star who, under Coach Pop‚Äôs leadership, led the Spurs to all five of their championships.

The toast is a way of expressing gratitude and humility. Yes, Coach Pop may be able to say he‚Äôs got the most wins as a coach. But he never forgets to give gratitude to his star player.

Humility helps us to grow. It makes us more approachable. It makes us more, well‚Ä¶human.

But, we‚Äôve all been on the opposite end of that story, too, haven‚Äôt we?

The one where someone else gets the credit. Where our name doesn‚Äôt make the toast, even though we helped build the table. Maybe it was at work, in a relationship, or even on a sports team ‚Äì that moment when your effort made something possible, but your contribution quietly disappeared behind someone else‚Äôs headline. 

It stings. Because we all want to feel seen for the part we play. But that‚Äôs also what makes Coach Pop‚Äôs ritual so powerful. He doesn‚Äôt just celebrate success, he shares it. And in a world obsessed with ownership, individuality, and visibility, humility can feel like a lost art. But the truth is, leadership without humility is just performance. The best leaders (the kind who build trust and loyalty that lasts decades) don‚Äôt need the spotlight to feel important. 

They happily, willingly, unreservedly shine it on others. 

And maybe that‚Äôs the real legacy worth toasting to.

Hey friends,

Quick thing before we start - we‚Äôre working on a content series +
some workshops aimed at teaching you the skills to build a
lifestyle business to get to financial + time freedom. If that
sounds vaguely interesting, please fill out this form (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/e5uoz0xvqmu7hlnezrqumi8dgz222blhvgzpn/reh8h9umvxox06i6/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVzdHlsZS1idXNpbmVzcy13YWl0bGlzdC8=
) to join the waitlist, and you‚Äôll be the first to hear when
things are ready üòä

Anyway, there‚Äôs an idea I‚Äôve been playing around with for the
past few weeks that I‚Äôd like to share with you. It might sound
simple, or even trite, but it‚Äôs been adding a lot of free
‚Äúhappiness points‚Äù to my life so I thought I‚Äôd share it.

It sort of stems from a lot of the ‚Äúspirituality‚Äù books I‚Äôve been
reading, and a bit from the meditation courses and lectures on
the Waking Up app.

If you‚Äôre practising non-dual meditation (the sort that the
Waking Up app teaches), the ‚Äústeps‚Äù are roughly as follows:

* You close your eyes and focus your attention on something like
your breath
* Great, now that you‚Äôve focused your attention on something like
your breath, you expand your awareness of sensations other than
your breath - the feel of the ground under you, the feel of your
clothing on your body etc
* Great, now that you‚Äôve done that, you recognise all of these
sensations as ‚Äúappearances in consciousness‚Äù - the shirt you‚Äôre
wearing is sending signals to the touch receptors on your skin,
which signals to your brain, and you ‚Äúexperience‚Äù those signals
as ‚Äúappearances‚Äù in your general awareness, and you interpret
them as ‚ÄúI‚Äôm wearing a piece of clothing on my chest‚Äù.
* When you have a thought, you realise that ‚Äúwait a minute, this
thought that I‚Äôm having is ALSO just an appearance in
consciousness‚Äù. If you try and trace the thought back to its
origin, you find‚Ä¶ nothing. Just like the feel of the wind on your
skin, or the sound of a police siren in the background, the
thought simply ‚Äúarises within consciousness‚Äù and then passes
away.
* Okay cool, so now you ‚Äúlook for who‚Äôs looking‚Äù, you try and
identify Who is actually doing all this meditating and all this
noticing of appearances in consciousness. And when you ‚Äúlook for
who‚Äôs looking‚Äù, you realise‚Ä¶ there‚Äôs nothing to find. The feeling
of being a person, the feeling of being an ‚ÄúI‚Äù that‚Äôs doing the
meditating‚Ä¶ that too is just an appearance in consciousness. This
is the ‚Äúmove‚Äù or the ‚Äústep‚Äù that I‚Äôve yet to actually experience
for myself, but apparently once you ‚Äúlook for the looker‚Äù and you
realise there‚Äôs nothing to find, then you become enlightened or
something and you feel one with everything or something like
that.

This isn‚Äôt a newsletter about meditation or enlightenment (not
yet anyway hehe), so of course, there‚Äôs going to be a more
worldly ‚Äúhack‚Äù that I‚Äôm going to share.

Here goes - everything we experience is simply an appearance in
consciousness.

There‚Äôs some sort of deep spiritual Truth there apparently, but I
haven‚Äôt yet reached that level‚Ä¶ instead, I use this insight to
make myself happier and more grateful each day.

Here‚Äôs how.

A couple of years ago, during my book launch period, I needed to
fly from Sydney to London, and I found a Singapore Airlines
flight where their First Class Suites were available for a hefty
but not insane price. I decided: ‚Äúyou know what, I‚Äôm going to
treat myself‚Äù and bought a ticket (see I told you I wasn‚Äôt
spiritually enlightened).

I‚Äôd never flown First Class before, and I was intent on savouring
the entire experience. I had a whole ‚Äúroom‚Äù all to myself, and it
had a chair in it, and you could recline on the chair and stretch
your legs out! They even had a bed in the suite, but I didn‚Äôt use
it because I wanted to properly savour the experience without
sleeping through it.

So I spent the flight reclining on this sofa chair thing, doing
some work on my laptop. I think I watched a movie too. The usual
stuff.

That was like 2 years ago (end of 2023). But a couple of weeks
ago, I was reclining on my couch in my living room, with my
laptop on my lap, doing some work. I‚Äôd done a Waking Up
meditation that morning that was all about ‚Äúrecognising that
literally everything is an appearance in consciousness‚Äù.

It got me thinking: I‚Äôm currently lying on the couch, typing
stuff on my laptop. The sensations of the couch behind me, and
the sensations of my laptop slightly heating my groin area - all
these sensations are just appearances in consciousness. Cool.

But‚Ä¶ wait a minute. 2 years ago, the first and (so far) last time
in my life that I‚Äôve flown First Class‚Ä¶ I spent that entire
flight lying on the couch, typing stuff on my laptop. I had the
sensations of the aeroplane chair behind me, and the sensations
of my laptop slightly heating my groin area‚Ä¶ all those sensations
were also just appearances in consciousness.

Wait a minute‚Ä¶ chilling on the couch in my living room‚Ä¶ feels
EXACTLY the same as chilling on the stupidly expensive 1A seat in
the Singapore Airlines First Class Suites‚Ä¶ both are just
appearances in consciousness, but they‚Äôre appearances in
consciousness that feel EXACTLY THE SAME. And I paid a few grand
for the First Class experience, and quite enjoyed it‚Ä¶ could I do
the same for the day-to-day experience of lying on my living room
couch?

I tried it out. While typing away on my laptop in my living room,
I imagined that I was back on that Singapore Airlines flight‚Ä¶ and
noticed another REALLY COOL thing - that actually, the experience
of lying on my couch, is actually BETTER than the experience of
being on an expensive First Class flight!

Why? Well, my sofa at home is more comfortable than the chairs
they‚Äôve got on aeroplanes. I can get up whenever I want, wander
over to the kitchen and make myself a nice coffee with the
Aeropress. Can‚Äôt do that on an aeroplane. Whenever I want, I can
wander into the bathroom, sit myself on the toilet and scroll
Instagram for as long as I want, without an air hostess knocking
on the door and asking if everything‚Äôs okay. Can‚Äôt do that on an
aeroplane, not even when flying First Class. When I‚Äôm at home, I
can pop down to the local coffee shop to grab a matcha latte.
Can‚Äôt do that on Singapore Airlines - all they have is coffee.

The experience of flying First Class on Singapore Airlines, which
costs several thousand dollars (if not more), is (a) just a
series of appearances in consciousness, and (b) those appearances
in consciousness are actually LESS PLEASANT than the experience
of living my day to day life.

And yet‚Ä¶ how often do we feel good about expensive experiences,
and how seldom do we feel grateful for the experience we have in
our own home?

I‚Äôve been applying this insight in other areas too:

* If I close my eyes, lying in my bathtub at home feels (almost)
identical to lying in a natural hot spring onsen in a fancy hotel
in Japan.
* If I close my eyes, having a shower at home feels identical to
having a shower in the fanciest spa in the world.
* If I close my eyes, drying myself after said shower feels
identical to drying myself on the poolside of the fanciest resort
in the world.

You get the idea.

I‚Äôm sure there‚Äôs some deeper spiritual meaning here that I‚Äôm
missing (if you know what it is, please feel free to reply to
this email) but over the past few weeks since realising this,
I‚Äôve gotten a lot of pleasure from comparing the sensations of my
day-to-day life with much-more-fancy-and-expensive experiences
that I‚Äôve had on trips and holidays, and realised: ‚Äúhuh, day to
day life is actually really awesome‚Äù.

Maybe you‚Äôve gotten to the end of this email and you‚Äôre rolling
your eyes because this is really obvious, and of course you
remember to be grateful for the experience of your day to day
life many many times each day.

But in case you‚Äôre anything like me, and you sometimes forget to
appreciate the simple pleasures of day-to-day life, maybe this
little ‚Äúappearances in consciousness‚Äù hack might be useful.

Next time you‚Äôre having a shower, or lying in bed, or just
chilling on the sofa with your laptop, try this: close your eyes
for a moment and notice the sensations. Then ask yourself - ‚Äúwhen
have I paid good money to have an experience that feels similar
to this?‚Äù

Maybe lying in bed feels like lying on that expensive
mongoose-albatross-feather hotel mattress from your last holiday.
Maybe your morning shower feels like that fancy spa treatment you
treated yourself to last year. Maybe sitting in your garden with
a cup of coffee feels just as good as sitting in that overpriced
caf√© you went to in Paris.

For me, I‚Äôve found that this little mental shift has made me way
more grateful for the stuff I get to experience every single day,
for free, at home. Without having to pay exorbitant sums for a
First Class Singapore Airlines flight (although if anyone who
works at a fancy airline is reading this, I‚Äôm sure YOUR
aircraft‚Äôs seats are MUCH better than my sofa at home).

Have a great week!

Ali xx

column7: (1/6) Welcome to LangSmith! Log Your First Trace üéâ
column9:
Welcome to LangSmith ‚Äì we‚Äôre thrilled to have you here!

Building LLM apps is exciting, but we know it can also be hard. Getting LLMs to respond appropriately can feel more art than science at times, so we built LangSmith to help.

LangSmith is here to support you at every step of your development journey with tools for observability, evaluation, and prompt engineering.

As you start building your app, you may need to debug unexpected outputs or performance bottlenecks. That‚Äôs where tracing in LangSmith comes in.

Tracing can help you pinpoint issues and track how each part of your application contributes to the output. You can also share traces with your team for seamless debugging.

Ready to log your first trace in LangSmith? ü§ì Watch this quick 5-minute video and see how easy it is to get started: https://track.pstmrk.it/3ts/youtu.be%2FHab2CV_0hpQ/Tpyp/lRS-AQ/AQ/4aa0e128-b64a-4fe7-99c5-3220ee54d43a/6/QMaKWbQmnX and follow along with the code here: https://track.pstmrk.it/3ts/github.com%2Fnhuang-lc%2Flangsmith-onboarding%2Ftree%2Fmain./Tpyp/lRS-AQ/AQ/4aa0e128-b64a-4fe7-99c5-3220ee54d43a/7/hVnenKATyb

If you need a hand getting started, our Quick Start (https://docs.smith.langchain.com/) and Tracing docs (https://docs.smith.langchain.com/observability/how_to_guides#tracing-configuration) have you covered ü•≥

Over the next 6 emails in our onboarding series, we‚Äôll dive into LangSmith‚Äôs core features and show you how to use them. I‚Äôll be back soon with more on the LangSmith Playground!
